00:20:11,670 --> 00:20:13,860
and the most precise of those tools.

521
00:20:13,860 --> 00:20:15,320
Now, let's talk about
how light is converted

522
00:20:15,320 --> 00:20:17,090
into biological signals.

523
00:20:17,090 --> 00:20:19,650
There's several ways in
which that is accomplished,

524
00:20:19,650 --> 00:20:22,220
but the fundamental thing to understand

525
00:20:22,220 --> 00:20:26,053
is this notion of
absorption of light energy.

526
00:20:26,950 --> 00:20:30,460
Certain pigments or colors

527
00:20:30,460 --> 00:20:33,830
in the thing that is
receiving the light energy,

528
00:20:33,830 --> 00:20:37,410
meaning the thing that
the light energy lands on,

529
00:20:37,410 --> 00:20:40,510
are going to absorb particular
wavelengths of light.

530
00:20:40,510 --> 00:20:43,370
Now, I promise you that you
already intuitively know

531
00:20:43,370 --> 00:20:44,740
how this works.

532
00:20:44,740 --> 00:20:47,310
For instance, if you were to sit outside

533
00:20:47,310 --> 00:20:49,190
on a very bright sunny day,

534
00:20:49,190 --> 00:20:52,560
and you had a table in
front of you that was metal,

535
00:20:52,560 --> 00:20:55,020
you might find it hard to
look down at that metal table

536
00:20:55,020 --> 00:20:56,950
because it's reflecting a lot of light

537
00:20:56,950 --> 00:20:58,250
of particular wavelengths.

538
00:20:59,260 --> 00:21:02,040
If that table were pitch black, however,

539
00:21:02,040 --> 00:21:04,570
it wouldn't reflect quite as much,

540
00:21:04,570 --> 00:21:07,120
and you would be able to
comfortably look at at it.

541
00:21:08,020 --> 00:21:10,900
If that table were red, it
might be somewhere in between.

542
00:21:10,900 --> 00:21:12,870
If that table were green,

543
00:21:12,870 --> 00:21:14,730
it would be also somewhere in between,

544
00:21:14,730 --> 00:21:16,550
but let's say it were very light blue.

545
00:21:16,550 --> 00:21:19,760
Well, then it might reflect
almost as much as a table

546
00:21:19,760 --> 00:21:23,440
that were just metal or
a white table surface.

547
00:21:23,440 --> 00:21:26,460
So the absorbance properties
of a given surface

548
00:21:26,460 --> 00:21:30,230
will determine whether or not
light energy goes and stays

549
00:21:30,230 --> 00:21:33,310
at that location and has
an impact on that location

550
00:21:33,310 --> 00:21:35,233
or whether or not it bounces off.

551
00:21:36,370 --> 00:21:38,760
Every biological function of light

552
00:21:38,760 --> 00:21:43,080
has to do with the absorbance
or the reflectance of light

553
00:21:43,080 --> 00:21:46,820
or light passing through
that particular thing,

554
00:21:46,820 --> 00:21:49,983
meaning that particular cell
or compartment within a cell.

555
00:21:51,910 --> 00:21:53,560
I'd like to make it clear how this works

556
00:21:53,560 --> 00:21:55,870
by using the three primary examples

557
00:21:55,870 --> 00:21:58,960
of how you take light in your environment

558
00:21:58,960 --> 00:22:01,643
and convert it into biological events.

559
00:22:03,080 --> 00:22:05,990
We have photoreceptors
in the back of our eyes.

560
00:22:05,990 --> 00:22:08,720
These photoreceptors
come in two major types,

561
00:22:08,720 --> 00:22:10,380
the so-called rods and the cones.

562
00:22:10,380 --> 00:22:13,120
The rods are very elongated,
they look like rods.

563
00:22:13,120 --> 00:22:16,010
And the cones look like little triangles.

564
00:22:16,010 --> 00:22:20,840
Rods and cones have
within them photopigment.

565
00:22:20,840 --> 00:22:24,340
They have dark stuff that's
stacked up in little layers.

566
00:22:24,340 --> 00:22:27,410
Rods absorb light of
essentially any wavelength.

567
00:22:27,410 --> 00:22:28,760
There's some variation to that,

568
00:22:28,760 --> 00:22:32,060
but let's just say rods don't care

569
00:22:32,060 --> 00:22:34,930
about the different colors of light.

570
00:22:34,930 --> 00:22:37,730
They will absorb light
energy, photon energy,

571
00:22:37,730 --> 00:22:40,030
if it's red, if it's green, if it's blue,

572
00:22:40,030 --> 00:22:42,100
if it's yellow, doesn't matter,

573
00:22:42,100 --> 00:22:44,210
as long as that light is bright enough.

574
00:22:44,210 --> 00:22:46,530
And it turns out that rods
are very, very sensitive.

575
00:22:46,530 --> 00:22:50,810
They can detect very, very
small numbers of photons.

576
00:22:50,810 --> 00:22:53,190
And rods are essentially what you use

577
00:22:53,190 --> 00:22:55,430
to see in very low light conditions.

578
00:22:55,430 --> 00:22:57,470
We'll return more to vision later.

579
00:22:57,470 --> 00:23:00,950
The cones come in three major varieties.

580
00:23:00,950 --> 00:23:02,990
At least for most people
who aren't colorblind,

581
00:23:02,990 --> 00:23:05,330
you have so-called red cones,
green cones, and blue cones.

582
00:23:05,330 --> 00:23:06,850
But they're not really
red, green, and blue

583
00:23:06,850 --> 00:23:07,940
in the back of your eye.

584
00:23:07,940 --> 00:23:10,180
They are cones that either absorb

585
00:23:10,180 --> 00:23:13,020
long wavelength light, red,

586
00:23:13,020 --> 00:23:16,120
that absorb medium
wavelength light, green,

587
00:23:16,120 --> 00:23:18,203
or short wavelength light, blue.

588
00:23:19,720 --> 00:23:21,290
The reason that they can absorb

589
00:23:21,290 --> 00:23:22,640
different wavelengths of light

590
00:23:22,640 --> 00:23:24,770
is they have different photopigments.

591
00:23:24,770 --> 00:23:26,960
So much as the example I gave before,

592
00:23:26,960 --> 00:23:29,630
where you have different tables outside

593
00:23:29,630 --> 00:23:30,820
in the sunny environment,

594
00:23:30,820 --> 00:23:32,700
and some are reflecting
light more than others,

595
00:23:32,700 --> 00:23:35,500
others are absorbing
light more than others,

596
00:23:35,500 --> 00:23:39,310
well, so too, the photoreceptors,
meaning the cones,

597
00:23:39,310 --> 00:23:42,310
are absorbing light of
different wavelengths

598
00:23:42,310 --> 00:23:43,760
to different extents.

599
00:23:43,760 --> 00:23:46,600
And in an absolutely incredible way,

600
00:23:46,600 --> 00:23:49,030
your brain is actually able
to take that information

601
00:23:49,030 --> 00:23:51,420
and create this perception
that we have of color.

602
00:23:51,420 --> 00:23:52,870
But that's another story altogether

603
00:23:52,870 --> 00:23:55,510
that we'll just touch on
a little bit more later,

604
00:23:55,510 --> 00:23:57,070
but that if you want to learn all about,

605
00:23:57,070 --> 00:23:59,893
you can go to our episode on vision.

606
00:24:01,200 --> 00:24:03,790
So that's photoreceptors
in the back of your eye,

607
00:24:03,790 --> 00:24:07,150
absorbing light of different
wavelengths, rods, and cones.

608
00:24:07,150 --> 00:24:08,210
The other place, of course,

609
00:24:08,210 --> 00:24:10,010
where light can impact our body

610
00:24:10,010 --> 00:24:12,670
is on our surface, on our skin.

611
00:24:12,670 --> 00:24:14,670
And skin has pigment too.

612
00:24:14,670 --> 00:24:17,010
We call that pigment melanin.

613
00:24:17,010 --> 00:24:19,890
We have within our skin
multiple cell types,

614
00:24:19,890 --> 00:24:23,100
but in the top layer of skin,
which is called the epidermis,

615
00:24:23,100 --> 00:24:27,400
we have keratinocytes,
and we have melanocytes.

616
00:24:27,400 --> 00:24:29,740
And the melanocytes are the cells

617
00:24:29,740 --> 00:24:31,390
that create pigmentation of the skin.

618
00:24:31,390 --> 00:24:34,800
And of course there is wide
variation in the degree

619
00:24:34,800 --> 00:24:37,200
to which there is
pigmentation of the skin,

620
00:24:37,200 --> 00:24:38,630
which has to do with genetics,

621
00:24:38,630 --> 00:24:41,140
also has to do with where
you were born and raised,

622
00:24:41,140 --> 00:24:43,760
how much light exposure you
have throughout the year, right?

623
00:24:43,760 --> 00:24:45,040
So people toward the equator

624
00:24:45,040 --> 00:24:46,940
tend to have more melanocyte activity

625
00:24:46,940 --> 00:24:49,410
than people who are
located at the North Pole.

626
00:24:49,410 --> 00:24:51,300
And of course, people live
at different locations

627
00:24:51,300 --> 00:24:52,133
throughout the Earth,

628
00:24:52,133 --> 00:24:53,960
regardless of their genetic background

629
00:24:53,960 --> 00:24:54,890
or where they were born.

630
00:24:54,890 --> 00:24:58,420
And so, as you all know,
with light exposure,

631
00:24:58,420 --> 00:25:02,600
those melanocytes will
turn on genetic programs

632
00:25:02,600 --> 00:25:04,410
and other biological programs

633
00:25:04,410 --> 00:25:06,770
that lead to enhanced
pigmentation of the skin,

634
00:25:06,770 --> 00:25:08,770
which we call tanning.

635
00:25:08,770 --> 00:25:12,750
The way they do that is by
absorbing UV light specifically.

636
00:25:12,750 --> 00:25:14,230
So with melanocytes,

637
00:25:14,230 --> 00:25:16,630
we have a very specific example

638
00:25:16,630 --> 00:25:20,330
of how a pigment absorbs
light of a particular length,

639
00:25:20,330 --> 00:25:23,250
in this case, ultraviolet
shortwave length light,

640
00:25:23,250 --> 00:25:26,910
which in turn creates a
set of biological signals

641
00:25:26,910 --> 00:25:29,590
within those cells that
in turn creates changes

642
00:25:29,590 --> 00:25:31,040
in our skin pigmentation.

643
00:25:31,040 --> 00:25:33,333
So we have photoreceptors,
we have melanocytes.

644
00:25:33,333 --> 00:25:35,290
And the third example I'd like to provide

645
00:25:35,290 --> 00:25:37,620
is that of every cell of your body.

646
00:25:37,620 --> 00:25:40,380
And what I mean by that is
that every cell of your body,

647
00:25:40,380 --> 00:25:44,590
meaning a cell that is
part of your bone tissue

648
00:25:44,590 --> 00:25:48,800
or your bone marrow or heart
tissue or liver or spleen,

649
00:25:48,800 --> 00:25:51,560
if light can access those cells,

650
00:25:51,560 --> 00:25:53,830
it will change the way
that those cells function

651
00:25:53,830 --> 00:25:55,363
for better or for worse.

652
00:25:56,540 --> 00:25:58,680
For many organs within our body

653
00:25:58,680 --> 00:26:02,110
that reside deep to our skin,

654
00:26:02,110 --> 00:26:05,360
light never arrives at those cells.

655
00:26:05,360 --> 00:26:06,690
A really good example of this

656
00:26:06,690 --> 00:26:09,440
that we'll touch on later is the spleen.

657
00:26:09,440 --> 00:26:12,590
Unless you have massive
damage to your body surface,

658
00:26:12,590 --> 00:26:14,790
unless you literally
have a hole in your body,

659
00:26:14,790 --> 00:26:18,100
light will never land
directly on your spleen,

660
00:26:18,100 --> 00:26:21,800
but the spleen still
responds to light information

661
00:26:21,800 --> 00:26:24,140
through indirect pathways.

662
00:26:24,140 --> 00:26:26,420
And those indirect pathways arise

663
00:26:26,420 --> 00:26:28,230
through light arriving on the skin

664
00:26:28,230 --> 00:26:30,650
and light arriving on the eyes.

665
00:26:30,650 --> 00:26:31,810
So a key principle

666
00:26:31,810 --> 00:26:34,570
that I'm going to return
to again and again today

667
00:26:34,570 --> 00:26:38,630
is that the ways in which
light can impact the biology

668
00:26:38,630 --> 00:26:40,640
of your organelles, your cells,

669
00:26:40,640 --> 00:26:43,530
your organs, and the tissues,
and indeed your whole body,

670
00:26:43,530 --> 00:26:45,410
can either be direct,

671
00:26:45,410 --> 00:26:48,280
so for instance, light onto
your skin impacting skin

672
00:26:48,280 --> 00:26:49,830
or light onto your photoreceptors

673
00:26:49,830 --> 00:26:52,100
impacting the photoreceptors of your eye,

674
00:26:52,100 --> 00:26:53,920
or it can be indirect.

675
00:26:53,920 --> 00:26:56,950
It can be light arriving
on your photoreceptors,

676
00:26:56,950 --> 00:26:59,910
the photoreceptors then
informing another cell type,

677
00:26:59,910 --> 00:27:01,780
which informs another cell type,

678
00:27:01,780 --> 00:27:03,220
which then relays a signal

679
00:27:03,220 --> 00:27:05,620
in kind of a bucket brigade manner

680
00:27:05,620 --> 00:27:07,577
off to the spleen and says to the spleen,

681
00:27:07,577 --> 00:27:10,400
"Hey, there's a lot of UV light out here.

682
00:27:10,400 --> 00:27:12,110
We're actually under stress.

683
00:27:12,110 --> 00:27:13,730
In fact, there's so much UV light

684
00:27:13,730 --> 00:27:16,750
that you need to activate
an immune program

685
00:27:16,750 --> 00:27:18,150
to protect the skin."

686
00:27:18,150 --> 00:27:19,210
And in response to that,

687
00:27:19,210 --> 00:27:21,960
the spleen can deploy certain
signals in certain cell types

688
00:27:21,960 --> 00:27:23,640
to go out and start repairing skin

689
00:27:23,640 --> 00:27:25,440
that's being damaged by UV light.

690
00:27:25,440 --> 00:27:28,420
So we have direct signals
and we have indirect signals,

691
00:27:28,420 --> 00:27:31,000
but in every case,

692
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:34,310
it starts with light of
particular wavelengths

693
00:27:34,310 --> 00:27:37,920
being absorbed by particular
pigments or properties

694
00:27:37,920 --> 00:27:42,330
of the surfaces that
those light waves land on.

695
00:27:42,330 --> 00:27:43,870
And as you recall from our discussion

696
00:27:43,870 --> 00:27:45,640
about the physics of light, remember,

697
00:27:45,640 --> 00:27:47,500
it's not just about light impinging

698
00:27:47,500 --> 00:27:48,590
on the surface of your body.

699
00:27:48,590 --> 00:27:51,980
Light can actually
penetrate deep to the skin

700
00:27:51,980 --> 00:27:55,830
and access at least certain
tissues and cells of your body.

701
00:27:55,830 --> 00:27:58,430
Even though you can't see
those wavelengths of light,

702
00:27:58,430 --> 00:28:01,020
they are getting into you all the time.

703
00:28:01,020 --> 00:28:04,110
So perhaps the best way
to wrap this discussion

704
00:28:04,110 --> 00:28:06,150
about the physics and the biology of light

705
00:28:06,150 --> 00:28:07,850
with a bit of a bow

706
00:28:07,850 --> 00:28:11,270
is to think about light as a transducer,

707
00:28:11,270 --> 00:28:13,930
meaning a communicator of what's going on

708
00:28:13,930 --> 00:28:15,760
in the environment around you

709
00:28:15,760 --> 00:28:19,150
and that some of those signals
are arriving at the surface

710
00:28:19,150 --> 00:28:21,270
and impacting the surface of your body.

711
00:28:21,270 --> 00:28:24,100
But many of those signals
are being taken by cells

712
00:28:24,100 --> 00:28:25,830
at the surface of your body,

713
00:28:25,830 --> 00:28:27,630
meaning your melanocytes in your skin

714
00:28:27,630 --> 00:28:29,480
and the photoreceptors of your eyes,

715
00:28:29,480 --> 00:28:33,350
and then being passed off
as a set of instructions

716
00:28:33,350 --> 00:28:35,760
to the other organs and
tissues of your body.

717
00:28:35,760 --> 00:28:38,980
Light can impact our biology in very fast,

718
00:28:38,980 --> 00:28:41,520
moderately fast, and slow ways.

719
00:28:41,520 --> 00:28:45,230
But even the slow ways in which
light can impact our biology

720
00:28:45,230 --> 00:28:48,370
can be very powerful
and very long-lasting.

721
00:28:48,370 --> 00:28:51,770
Just as a quick example
of the rapid effects

722
00:28:51,770 --> 00:28:53,950
of light on our biology,

723
00:28:53,950 --> 00:28:58,360
if you were to go from a room
that is dimly lit or dark

724
00:28:58,360 --> 00:29:01,110
into a very brightly lit room,

725
00:29:01,110 --> 00:29:04,600
you would immediately feel very alert.

726
00:29:04,600 --> 00:29:05,990
You might say, "No, that's the not true.

727
00:29:05,990 --> 00:29:09,080
Sometimes I wake up and it's
dark, and I kind of stumble out

728
00:29:09,080 --> 00:29:11,030
and it's lighter out in the next room.

729
00:29:11,030 --> 00:29:12,530
And it takes me a while to wake up."

730
00:29:12,530 --> 00:29:15,080
Ah, but if we were to move you from a room

731
00:29:15,080 --> 00:29:17,100
that was very dark to very bright,

732
00:29:17,100 --> 00:29:19,890
a signal conveyed from your eyes

733
00:29:19,890 --> 00:29:23,170
to an area of your brain stem
called the locus coeruleus

734
00:29:23,170 --> 00:29:25,780
would cause the release of adrenaline

735
00:29:25,780 --> 00:29:27,520
similar to the release of adrenaline

736
00:29:27,520 --> 00:29:30,010
if you were to be dropped
into very, very cold water

737
00:29:30,010 --> 00:29:30,910
all of a sudden.

738
00:29:30,910 --> 00:29:33,550
Just an immediate wake-up
signal to your brain and body.

739
00:29:33,550 --> 00:29:35,900
So that's an example of a rapid effect

740
00:29:35,900 --> 00:29:37,550
of light on your biology,

741
00:29:37,550 --> 00:29:39,760
not a very typical one, but nonetheless,

742
00:29:39,760 --> 00:29:42,543
one that has a hardwired
biological mechanism.

743
00:29:43,530 --> 00:29:45,560
At the other end of the spectrum

744
00:29:45,560 --> 00:29:48,490
are what we call slow
integrating effects of light

745
00:29:48,490 --> 00:29:49,980
on our biology.

746
00:29:49,980 --> 00:29:53,320
So what I mean by that are
ways in which your body

747
00:29:53,320 --> 00:29:56,640
is taking information about
light in the environment,

748
00:29:56,640 --> 00:29:59,760
not in the sort of snapshot, acute sense,

749
00:29:59,760 --> 00:30:02,540
but averaging the amount of
light in your environment.

750
00:30:02,540 --> 00:30:05,280
And that average light information

751
00:30:05,280 --> 00:30:07,970
is changing the way
that your biology works.

752
00:30:07,970 --> 00:30:10,650
But even though this is a slow process,

753
00:30:10,650 --> 00:30:13,490
as I mentioned before,
it's a very powerful one.

754
00:30:13,490 --> 00:30:15,530
The primary example of this

755
00:30:15,530 --> 00:30:18,340
are so-called circannual rhythms.

756
00:30:18,340 --> 00:30:21,880
Circannual rhythms are
literally a calendar

757
00:30:21,880 --> 00:30:26,450
that exists within your
body that uses not numbers,

758
00:30:26,450 --> 00:30:28,870
but amounts of hormone that are released

759
00:30:28,870 --> 00:30:31,870
into your brain and body
each day and each night

760
00:30:31,870 --> 00:30:34,130
as a way of knowing where you are

761
00:30:34,130 --> 00:30:37,560
in the 365-day calendar year.

762
00:30:37,560 --> 00:30:40,960
Now that might seem kind of
crazy, but it's not crazy.

763
00:30:40,960 --> 00:30:45,070
The Earth travels around
the sun once every 365 days.

764
00:30:45,070 --> 00:30:49,143
And depending on where you are
on the Earth, where you live,

765
00:30:50,270 --> 00:30:54,920
you are going to get more or
less light each day on average,

766
00:30:54,920 --> 00:30:56,560
depending on the time of year.

767
00:30:56,560 --> 00:30:58,850
So if you're in the Northern Hemisphere,

768
00:30:58,850 --> 00:31:02,940
in the winter months, days are
shorter, nights are longer.

769
00:31:02,940 --> 00:31:06,040
In the summer months, days are
longer, nights are shorter.

770
00:31:06,040 --> 00:31:09,100
And of course, things
change whether or not you're

771
00:31:09,100 --> 00:31:11,700
in the Northern Hemisphere
or the Southern Hemisphere,

772
00:31:11,700 --> 00:31:16,640
but nonetheless in short
days you have more darkness,

773
00:31:16,640 --> 00:31:17,880
that's obvious.

774
00:31:17,880 --> 00:31:22,680
And if you understand that
light arriving on the eyes

775
00:31:23,880 --> 00:31:26,190
is absorbed by a particular cell type

776
00:31:26,190 --> 00:31:29,050
called the intrinsically
photosensitive ganglion cell.

777
00:31:29,050 --> 00:31:29,883
It's just a name.

778
00:31:29,883 --> 00:31:31,190
You don't need to know
the name, but if you want,

779
00:31:31,190 --> 00:31:32,350
it's the so-called intrinsically

780
00:31:32,350 --> 00:31:33,480
photosensitive ganglion cell,

781
00:31:33,480 --> 00:31:35,330
also called the melanopsin cell

782
00:31:35,330 --> 00:31:36,810
because it contains an opsin,

783
00:31:36,810 --> 00:31:41,810
a photopigment that absorbs
shortwave length light

784
00:31:41,960 --> 00:31:43,730
that arrives through sunlight.

785
00:31:43,730 --> 00:31:47,510
Those cells communicate to
particular stations in the brain

786
00:31:47,510 --> 00:31:51,680
that in turn connect to
your so-called pineal gland,

787
00:31:51,680 --> 00:31:53,430
which is this little pea-sized gland

788
00:31:53,430 --> 00:31:54,700
in the middle of your brain

789
00:31:54,700 --> 00:31:57,650
that releases a hormone called melatonin.

790
00:31:57,650 --> 00:32:00,450
And the only thing you
need to know is that light

791
00:32:00,450 --> 00:32:02,210
activates these particular cells,

792
00:32:02,210 --> 00:32:04,550
the intrinsically
photosensitive melanopsin cells,

793
00:32:04,550 --> 00:32:08,460
which in turn shuts down
the production of melatonin

794
00:32:08,460 --> 00:32:09,653
from the pineal gland.

795
00:32:11,020 --> 00:32:13,910
If you think about this
in terms of the travel

796
00:32:13,910 --> 00:32:16,980
of the Earth around the
sun across the year,

797
00:32:16,980 --> 00:32:19,600
what it means is that in short days,

798
00:32:19,600 --> 00:32:22,080
because there's very
little light on average

799
00:32:22,080 --> 00:32:23,713
landing on these cells,

800
00:32:24,730 --> 00:32:28,170
the duration of melatonin
release will be much longer

801
00:32:28,170 --> 00:32:30,860
because as I mentioned
before, light inhibits,

802
00:32:30,860 --> 00:32:32,580
it shuts down melatonin.

803
00:32:32,580 --> 00:32:36,100
Whereas in the summer months,
much more light on average

804
00:32:36,100 --> 00:32:37,580
will land on your eyes, right?

805
00:32:37,580 --> 00:32:39,010
Because days are longer.

806
00:32:39,010 --> 00:32:40,450
Even if you're spending more time indoors,

807
00:32:40,450 --> 00:32:43,540
on average, you're going to get more light

808
00:32:43,540 --> 00:32:45,160
to activate these cells.

809
00:32:45,160 --> 00:32:48,207
And because light shuts
down melatonin production,

810
00:32:48,207 --> 00:32:51,320
what you'll find is that the
duration of melatonin release

811
00:32:51,320 --> 00:32:54,420
for the pineal is much shorter.

812
00:32:54,420 --> 00:32:57,510
So melatonin is a transducer.

813
00:32:57,510 --> 00:33:00,630
It's a communicator of
how much light on average

814
00:33:00,630 --> 00:33:03,000
is in your physical environment.

815
00:33:03,000 --> 00:33:05,090
What this means is

816
00:33:05,090 --> 00:33:07,460
for people living in
the Northern Hemisphere,

817
00:33:07,460 --> 00:33:10,580
you're getting more melatonin
release in the winter months

818
00:33:10,580 --> 00:33:12,680
than you are in the summer months.

819
00:33:12,680 --> 00:33:17,680
So you have a calendar system
that is based in a hormone,

820
00:33:18,720 --> 00:33:22,159
and that hormone is using
light in order to determine

821
00:33:22,159 --> 00:33:26,200
where you are in that
journey around the sun.

822
00:33:26,200 --> 00:33:27,100
Now, this is beautiful.

823
00:33:27,100 --> 00:33:28,540
At least to me, it's beautiful

824
00:33:28,540 --> 00:33:31,900
because what it means is that
the environment around us

825
00:33:31,900 --> 00:33:33,870
is converted into a signal

826
00:33:33,870 --> 00:33:36,900
that changes the environment within us.

827
00:33:36,900 --> 00:33:38,820
That signal is melatonin,

828
00:33:38,820 --> 00:33:41,220
and melatonin is well known for its role

829
00:33:41,220 --> 00:33:42,950
in making us sleepy each night

830
00:33:42,950 --> 00:33:44,810
and allowing us to fall asleep.

831
00:33:44,810 --> 00:33:46,250
Many of you have probably heard before,

832
00:33:46,250 --> 00:33:48,930
I am not a big fan of
melatonin supplementation

833
00:33:48,930 --> 00:33:52,200
for a number of reasons,
but just as a quick aside,

834
00:33:52,200 --> 00:33:54,390
the levels of melatonin
that are in most supplements

835
00:33:54,390 --> 00:33:57,520
are far too high to really
be considered physiological.

836
00:33:57,520 --> 00:34:00,210
They are indeed super
physiological in most cases,

837
00:34:00,210 --> 00:34:02,960
and melatonin can have a
number of different effects,

838
00:34:02,960 --> 00:34:05,170
not just related to sleep,

839
00:34:05,170 --> 00:34:07,730
but that's supplemented melatonin.

840
00:34:07,730 --> 00:34:10,400
Here, I'm talking about
our natural production

841
00:34:10,400 --> 00:34:11,500
and release of melatonin

842
00:34:11,500 --> 00:34:15,793
according to where we are in
the 365-day calendar year.

843
00:34:17,130 --> 00:34:19,080
Endogenous melatonin,
meaning the melatonin

844
00:34:19,080 --> 00:34:20,960
that we make within our bodies naturally,

845
00:34:20,960 --> 00:34:23,610
not melatonin that's supplemented,

846
00:34:23,610 --> 00:34:26,800
has two general categories of effects.

847
00:34:26,800 --> 00:34:29,179
The first set of effects are
so called regulatory effects

848
00:34:29,179 --> 00:34:30,939
and the others are protective effects.

849
00:34:30,940 --> 00:34:32,830
The regulatory effects are for instance,

850
00:34:32,830 --> 00:34:37,580
that melatonin can
positively impact bone mass.

851
00:34:37,580 --> 00:34:39,350
So melatonin can, for instance,

852
00:34:39,350 --> 00:34:41,850
turn on the production of osteoblasts,

853
00:34:41,850 --> 00:34:45,870
which are essentially stem
cells that make more bone for us

854
00:34:45,870 --> 00:34:47,460
that make our bones stronger

855
00:34:47,460 --> 00:34:50,093
and that can replace
damaged aspects of our bone.

856
00:34:51,100 --> 00:34:53,250
Melatonin is also involved in maturation

857
00:34:53,250 --> 00:34:56,889
of the gonads during puberty,
the ovaries and the testes.

858
00:34:56,889 --> 00:34:58,650
Although there, the effects of melatonin

859
00:34:58,650 --> 00:35:01,330
tend to be suppressive on maturation

860
00:35:01,330 --> 00:35:02,820
of the ovaries and testes,

861
00:35:02,820 --> 00:35:04,660
meaning high levels of melatonin

862
00:35:04,660 --> 00:35:07,560
tend to reduce testicle volume

863
00:35:07,560 --> 00:35:10,920
and reduce certain
functions within the testes,

864
00:35:10,920 --> 00:35:13,630
including sperm production
and testosterone production.

865
00:35:13,630 --> 00:35:16,730
And within the ovaries,
melatonin can suppress

866
00:35:16,730 --> 00:35:18,630
the maturation of eggs, et cetera.

867
00:35:18,630 --> 00:35:20,080
Now, I don't want anyone to get scared

868
00:35:20,080 --> 00:35:21,590
if you've been taking melatonin.

869
00:35:21,590 --> 00:35:22,830
Most of the effects of melatonin

870
00:35:22,830 --> 00:35:25,220
on those functions are reversible,

871
00:35:25,220 --> 00:35:27,310
but I should point out
that one of the reasons

872
00:35:27,310 --> 00:35:30,670
why children don't go into
puberty until a particular age

873
00:35:30,670 --> 00:35:32,080
is that young children

874
00:35:32,080 --> 00:35:34,790
tend to have chronically
high endogenous melatonin.

875
00:35:34,790 --> 00:35:37,410
And that is healthy to
keep them out of puberty

876
00:35:37,410 --> 00:35:40,740
until it's the right time
for puberty to happen.

877
00:35:40,740 --> 00:35:43,440
So melatonin can increase bone mass,

878
00:35:43,440 --> 00:35:46,890
but reduces gonad mass, so to speak.

879
00:35:46,890 --> 00:35:48,770
It's going to have varying effects

880
00:35:48,770 --> 00:35:51,247
depending on the ratios and
levels of other hormones

881
00:35:51,247 --> 00:35:53,260
and other biological events in the body.

882
00:35:53,260 --> 00:35:54,170
But as you can see,

883
00:35:54,170 --> 00:35:57,570
melatonin has these powerful
regulatory on other tissues.

884
00:35:57,570 --> 00:36:00,910
I should also mention that
melatonin is a powerful modulator

885
00:36:00,910 --> 00:36:02,160
of placental development.

886
00:36:02,160 --> 00:36:03,520
So for anyone that's pregnant,

887
00:36:03,520 --> 00:36:05,880
if you're considering
melatonin supplementation,

888
00:36:05,880 --> 00:36:08,560
please, please, please
talk to your OB/GYN,

889
00:36:08,560 --> 00:36:11,010
talk to your other doctor as well.

890
00:36:11,010 --> 00:36:12,410
You want to be very, very cautious

891
00:36:12,410 --> 00:36:14,690
because of the powerful
effects that melatonin can have

892
00:36:14,690 --> 00:36:16,950
on the developing fetus and placenta.

893
00:36:16,950 --> 00:36:20,050
For people that are not
pregnant, in fact, all people,

894
00:36:20,050 --> 00:36:22,690
melatonin has a powerful effect

895
00:36:22,690 --> 00:36:24,990
on the central nervous system as a whole.

896
00:36:24,990 --> 00:36:27,020
Your brain and spinal cord
are the major components

897
00:36:27,020 --> 00:36:28,480
of your central nervous system ,

898
00:36:28,480 --> 00:36:32,193
and melatonin, because it's
associated with darkness,

899
00:36:33,070 --> 00:36:34,240
which is just another way of saying

900
00:36:34,240 --> 00:36:35,897
that light suppresses melatonin,

901
00:36:35,897 --> 00:36:39,230
melatonin is thereby
associated with the dark phase

902
00:36:39,230 --> 00:36:40,693
of each 24-hour cycle,

903
00:36:41,840 --> 00:36:43,890
it can have a number of different effects

904
00:36:44,750 --> 00:36:48,380
in terms of waking up or making
our body feel more sleepy.

905
00:36:48,380 --> 00:36:50,460
And it does that by way of impacting cells

906
00:36:50,460 --> 00:36:51,490
within our nervous system,

907
00:36:51,490 --> 00:36:54,090
literally turning on certain brain areas,

908
00:36:54,090 --> 00:36:55,620
turning off other brain areas.

909
00:36:55,620 --> 00:36:57,110
And it does that through a whole cascade

910
00:36:57,110 --> 00:36:58,520
of biological mechanisms,

911
00:36:58,520 --> 00:37:00,510
a bit too detailed to get into today.

912
00:37:00,510 --> 00:37:03,040
So melatonin is regulating
how awake or asleep we are.

913
00:37:03,040 --> 00:37:05,980
It tends to make us more
asleep, incidentally.

914
00:37:05,980 --> 00:37:08,880
It's regulating our timing of puberty,

915
00:37:08,880 --> 00:37:11,340
and it's regulating how our gonads,

916
00:37:11,340 --> 00:37:12,940
the testes and ovaries, function,

917
00:37:12,940 --> 00:37:14,830
even in adulthood, to some extent.

918
00:37:14,830 --> 00:37:17,460
And it's regulating bone mass.

919
00:37:17,460 --> 00:37:18,293
As I mentioned before,

920
00:37:18,293 --> 00:37:20,510
melatonin also has protective effects.

921
00:37:20,510 --> 00:37:22,210
It can activate our immune system.

922
00:37:22,210 --> 00:37:25,550
It is among the most potent antioxidants.

923
00:37:25,550 --> 00:37:28,180
So it is known to have
certain anti-cancer properties

924
00:37:28,180 --> 00:37:29,670
and things of that sort,

925
00:37:29,670 --> 00:37:32,170
which is not to say that you
simply want more melatonin.

926
00:37:32,170 --> 00:37:33,900
I think a lot of people get misled

927
00:37:33,900 --> 00:37:35,180
when they hear something like,

928
00:37:35,180 --> 00:37:38,010
melatonin has anti-cancer properties.

929
00:37:38,010 --> 00:37:40,500
That doesn't mean that cranking
up the levels of melatonin

930
00:37:40,500 --> 00:37:43,670
by supplementing it, or by
spending time in darkness

931
00:37:43,670 --> 00:37:44,560
and not getting any light,

932
00:37:44,560 --> 00:37:45,823
which would, of course, inhibit melatonin,

933
00:37:45,823 --> 00:37:48,540
is going to be beneficial
for combating cancer.

934
00:37:48,540 --> 00:37:50,590
That's not the way it works.

935
00:37:50,590 --> 00:37:54,050
It is actually the rise
and fall of melatonin

936
00:37:54,050 --> 00:37:55,690
every 24-hour cycle

937
00:37:55,690 --> 00:37:58,510
and the changes in the duration
of that melatonin signal

938
00:37:58,510 --> 00:37:59,870
throughout the seasons

939
00:37:59,870 --> 00:38:03,340
that has these anti-cancer
and antioxidant effects.

940
00:38:03,340 --> 00:38:07,140
So when we think about
light impacting our biology,

941
00:38:07,140 --> 00:38:08,700
the reason I bring up melatonin

942
00:38:08,700 --> 00:38:10,340
as the primary example of that

943
00:38:10,340 --> 00:38:12,953
is A, because melatonin impacts
so many important functions

944
00:38:12,953 --> 00:38:14,460
within our brain and body,

945
00:38:14,460 --> 00:38:17,870
but also because hormones
in general, not always,

946
00:38:17,870 --> 00:38:19,270
but in general, are responsible

947
00:38:19,270 --> 00:38:22,730
for these slow modulatory
effects on our biology.

948
00:38:22,730 --> 00:38:24,840
And so I'm using this as an example

949
00:38:24,840 --> 00:38:26,780
of how light throughout the year

950
00:38:26,780 --> 00:38:29,290
is changing the way
that the different cells

951
00:38:29,290 --> 00:38:31,100
and tissues and organs
of your body are working,

952
00:38:31,100 --> 00:38:34,340
and that melatonin is the
transducer of that signal.

953
00:38:34,340 --> 00:38:35,173
So at this point,

954
00:38:35,173 --> 00:38:38,090
we can say light powerfully
modulates melatonin,

955
00:38:38,090 --> 00:38:39,720
meaning it shuts down melatonin.

956
00:38:39,720 --> 00:38:42,470
Melatonin is both beneficial
for certain tissues

957
00:38:42,470 --> 00:38:46,280
and suppressive for other
tissues and functions.

958
00:38:46,280 --> 00:38:47,820
What should we do with this information?

959
00:38:47,820 --> 00:38:50,890
Well, it's very well established now

960
00:38:50,890 --> 00:38:53,130
that one of the best
things that we can all do

961
00:38:53,130 --> 00:38:56,630
is to get the proper amount
of sunlight each day.

962
00:38:56,630 --> 00:39:00,370
And by proper, I mean appropriate
for that time of year.

963
00:39:00,370 --> 00:39:03,600
So in the summer months
where the days are longer

964
00:39:03,600 --> 00:39:04,820
and nights are shorter,

965
00:39:04,820 --> 00:39:08,250
we would all do well to get
more sunlight in our eyes.

966
00:39:08,250 --> 00:39:10,140
And again, it's going to be to our eyes

967
00:39:10,140 --> 00:39:11,980
because as you recall,

968
00:39:11,980 --> 00:39:14,270
the pineal sits deep in the brain,

969
00:39:14,270 --> 00:39:16,360
and light can't access
the pineal directly,

970
00:39:16,360 --> 00:39:17,870
at least not in humans.

971
00:39:17,870 --> 00:39:22,650
So in order to get light
information to the pineal

972
00:39:22,650 --> 00:39:25,200
and thereby get the
proper levels of melatonin

973
00:39:26,160 --> 00:39:27,610
according to the time of year,

974
00:39:27,610 --> 00:39:30,960
we should all try and get
outside as much as possible

975
00:39:30,960 --> 00:39:34,200
during the long days of summer and spring.

976
00:39:34,200 --> 00:39:36,060
And in the winter months, it makes sense

977
00:39:36,060 --> 00:39:37,760
to spend more time indoors.

978
00:39:37,760 --> 00:39:38,840
For those of you that suffer

979
00:39:38,840 --> 00:39:40,200
from seasonal effective disorder,

980
00:39:40,200 --> 00:39:41,490
which is a seasonal depression,

981
00:39:41,490 --> 00:39:44,220
or feel low during the
fall and winter months,

982
00:39:44,220 --> 00:39:45,340
there are ways to offset this.

983
00:39:45,340 --> 00:39:47,920
We did an entire episode on
mood and circadian rhythms

984
00:39:47,920 --> 00:39:49,150
where we described this.

985
00:39:49,150 --> 00:39:50,500
So it does make sense for some people

986
00:39:50,500 --> 00:39:52,970
to get more bright light in
their eyes early in the morning

987
00:39:52,970 --> 00:39:56,050
and throughout the day during
the winter months as well.

988
00:39:56,050 --> 00:39:59,420
But nonetheless, changes in melatonin,

989
00:39:59,420 --> 00:40:01,090
meaning changes in the duration

990
00:40:01,090 --> 00:40:04,120
of melatonin release across the
year are normal and healthy.

991
00:40:04,120 --> 00:40:06,800
So provided that you're not
suffering from depression,

992
00:40:06,800 --> 00:40:09,570
it's going to be healthy to
somewhat modulate your amount

993
00:40:09,570 --> 00:40:11,690
of indoor and outdoor
time across the year.

994
00:40:11,690 --> 00:40:13,270
The other thing to understand

995
00:40:13,270 --> 00:40:15,080
is this very firmly established fact,

996
00:40:15,080 --> 00:40:18,173
which is light powerfully
inhibits melatonin.

997
00:40:19,310 --> 00:40:21,010
If you wake up in the middle of the night,

998
00:40:21,010 --> 00:40:23,360
and you go into the bathroom
and you flip on the lights,

999
00:40:23,360 --> 00:40:26,520
and those are very bright,
overhead, fluorescent lights,

1000
00:40:26,520 --> 00:40:28,090
your melatonin levels,

1001
00:40:28,090 --> 00:40:30,210
which would ordinarily be quite high

1002
00:40:30,210 --> 00:40:31,043
in the middle of the night

1003
00:40:31,043 --> 00:40:33,850
because you've been eyes
closed in the dark, presumably,

1004
00:40:33,850 --> 00:40:37,040
will immediately plummet
to near zero or zero.

1005
00:40:37,040 --> 00:40:40,080
We would all do well
regardless of time of year

1006
00:40:40,080 --> 00:40:44,410
to not destroy our melatonin
in the middle of the night

1007
00:40:44,410 --> 00:40:45,420
in this way.

1008
00:40:45,420 --> 00:40:46,990
So if you need to get up
in the middle of the night

1009
00:40:46,990 --> 00:40:47,823
and use the restroom,

1010
00:40:47,823 --> 00:40:50,920
which is a perfectly normal
behavior for many people,

1011
00:40:50,920 --> 00:40:53,990
use the minimum amount of light required

1012
00:40:53,990 --> 00:40:57,120
in order to safely move
through the environment

1013
00:40:57,120 --> 00:40:58,620
that you need to move through.

1014
00:40:59,780 --> 00:41:02,480
Melatonin needs to come
on early in the night.

1015
00:41:02,480 --> 00:41:06,330
It actually starts rising in
the evening and towards sleep.

1016
00:41:06,330 --> 00:41:08,250
But then as you close your
eyes and you go to sleep,

1017
00:41:08,250 --> 00:41:10,720
melatonin levels are
going to continue to rise

1018
00:41:10,720 --> 00:41:13,630
at least for several hours into the night.

1019
00:41:13,630 --> 00:41:15,250
Again, if you get up in
the middle of the night,

1020
00:41:15,250 --> 00:41:17,950
really try hard not to flip
on a lot of bright lights.

1021
00:41:17,950 --> 00:41:19,500
If you do that every once in a while,

1022
00:41:19,500 --> 00:41:21,060
it's not going to be a problem.

1023
00:41:21,060 --> 00:41:23,010
But if you're doing
that night after night,

1024
00:41:23,010 --> 00:41:27,490
you are really disrupting
this fundamental signal

1025
00:41:27,490 --> 00:41:29,030
that occurs every night,

1026
00:41:29,030 --> 00:41:31,130
regardless of winter,
spring, summer, et cetera.

1027
00:41:31,130 --> 00:41:33,530
And that is communicating information

1028
00:41:33,530 --> 00:41:37,100
about where your brain and
body should be in time.

1029
00:41:37,100 --> 00:41:38,920
And I know that's a little
bit of a tricky concept,

1030
00:41:38,920 --> 00:41:41,880
but really our body is
not meant to function

1031
00:41:41,880 --> 00:41:43,380
in the same way during the winter months,

1032
00:41:43,380 --> 00:41:44,570
as the summer months.

1033
00:41:44,570 --> 00:41:48,030
There are functions that
are specifically optimal

1034
00:41:48,030 --> 00:41:49,670
for the shorter days of winter.

1035
00:41:49,670 --> 00:41:51,840
And there are functions that
are specifically optimal

1036
00:41:51,840 --> 00:41:53,840
for the longer or days of summer.

1037
00:41:53,840 --> 00:41:58,560
So again, try to avoid bright
light exposure to your eyes

1038
00:41:58,560 --> 00:41:59,610
in the middle of the night.

1039
00:41:59,610 --> 00:42:01,610
And for those of you that
are doing shift work,

1040
00:42:01,610 --> 00:42:04,140
what I can say is try and
avoid getting bright light

1041
00:42:04,140 --> 00:42:06,100
in your eyes in the middle
of your sleep cycle.

1042
00:42:06,100 --> 00:42:07,470
So even if you're sleeping
in the middle of the day,

1043
00:42:07,470 --> 00:42:08,770
because you have to work at night,

1044
00:42:08,770 --> 00:42:11,210
if you wake up during that about of sleep,

1045
00:42:11,210 --> 00:42:13,390
really try hard to limit
the amount of light,

1046
00:42:13,390 --> 00:42:15,610
which is going to be harder
for shift workers, right?

1047
00:42:15,610 --> 00:42:17,450
Because there are generally
a lot more lights on

1048
00:42:17,450 --> 00:42:18,540
and bright lights outside,

1049
00:42:18,540 --> 00:42:20,100
so you would want to close the blinds

1050
00:42:20,100 --> 00:42:22,420
and limit artificial light inside.

1051
00:42:22,420 --> 00:42:25,980
One way to bypass some
of the inhibitory effects

1052
00:42:25,980 --> 00:42:27,450
of light on melatonin

1053
00:42:27,450 --> 00:42:30,010
is to change your physical environment

1054
00:42:30,010 --> 00:42:32,040
by, for instance, dimming the lights.

1055
00:42:32,040 --> 00:42:34,030
That's one simple way, very low-cost way.

1056
00:42:34,030 --> 00:42:35,810
In fact, you'll save money
by dimming the lights

1057
00:42:35,810 --> 00:42:36,750
or turning them off.

1058
00:42:36,750 --> 00:42:39,170
The other is if you
are going to use light,

1059
00:42:39,170 --> 00:42:41,870
using long wavelength light,
because, as you recall,

1060
00:42:41,870 --> 00:42:44,090
these intrinsically
photosensitive melanopsin cells

1061
00:42:44,090 --> 00:42:46,770
within your retina that convey the signal

1062
00:42:46,770 --> 00:42:49,070
about bright light in your environment

1063
00:42:49,070 --> 00:42:51,780
to impact melatonin,
to shut down melatonin,

1064
00:42:51,780 --> 00:42:53,890
respond to short wavelengths of light.

1065
00:42:53,890 --> 00:42:55,900
So red light is long wavelength light.

1066
00:42:55,900 --> 00:42:57,800
You now understand that
from our discussion

1067
00:42:57,800 --> 00:42:59,660
about the physics of light.

1068
00:42:59,660 --> 00:43:03,450
And if you were to use
amber-colored light or red light

1069
00:43:03,450 --> 00:43:06,730
and even better, dim
amber or dim red light

1070
00:43:06,730 --> 00:43:07,563
in the middle of the night,

1071
00:43:07,563 --> 00:43:11,130
well, then you would probably
not reduce melatonin at all

1072
00:43:11,130 --> 00:43:13,070
unless those red lights and amber lights

1073
00:43:13,070 --> 00:43:14,120
are very, very bright.

1074
00:43:14,120 --> 00:43:16,310
Any light, provided it's bright enough,

1075
00:43:16,310 --> 00:43:18,900
will shut down melatonin production.

1076
00:43:18,900 --> 00:43:20,757
One final point about melatonin,

1077
00:43:20,757 --> 00:43:24,010
and this relates to melatonin
supplementation as well,

1078
00:43:24,010 --> 00:43:25,960
is that now that you understand

1079
00:43:25,960 --> 00:43:28,110
how potently melatonin can impact things

1080
00:43:28,110 --> 00:43:29,950
like cardiovascular
function, immune function,

1081
00:43:29,950 --> 00:43:32,280
anti-cancer properties, bone mass,

1082
00:43:32,280 --> 00:43:34,370
gonad function, et cetera,

1083
00:43:34,370 --> 00:43:36,710
you can understand why it would make sense

1084
00:43:36,710 --> 00:43:39,010
to be cautious about
melatonin supplementation,

1085
00:43:39,010 --> 00:43:41,530
because supplementation
tends to be pretty static.

1086
00:43:41,530 --> 00:43:44,490
It's X number of milligrams per night,

1087
00:43:44,490 --> 00:43:48,350
whereas normally endogenously
the amount of melatonin

1088
00:43:48,350 --> 00:43:49,450
that you're releasing each night

1089
00:43:49,450 --> 00:43:52,170
is changing according to time of year,

1090
00:43:52,170 --> 00:43:54,370
or if you happen to live in an area

1091
00:43:54,370 --> 00:43:56,970
where there isn't much change
in day length across the year,

1092
00:43:56,970 --> 00:43:59,190
so for instance, if you
live near the equator,

1093
00:43:59,190 --> 00:44:02,730
well, then your body is accustomed
to having regular amounts

1094
00:44:02,730 --> 00:44:04,050
of melatonin each night.

1095
00:44:04,050 --> 00:44:06,210
When you start supplementing melatonin,

1096
00:44:06,210 --> 00:44:09,280
you start changing the total
amount of melatonin, obviously,

1097
00:44:09,280 --> 00:44:12,280
but you're also changing
the normal rhythms

1098
00:44:12,280 --> 00:44:15,030
in how much melatonin is being released

1099
00:44:15,030 --> 00:44:16,360
into your brain and body

1100
00:44:16,360 --> 00:44:19,050
across the 365-day calendar year.

1101
00:44:19,050 --> 00:44:20,230
So while I'm somebody

1102
00:44:20,230 --> 00:44:24,020
who readily embraces
supplementation in various forms,

1103
00:44:24,020 --> 00:44:26,410
for things like sleep
and focus, et cetera,

1104
00:44:26,410 --> 00:44:30,100
when it comes to melatonin,
I'm extremely cautious.

1105
00:44:30,100 --> 00:44:32,610
And I think it's also
one of the few examples

1106
00:44:32,610 --> 00:44:35,860
where a hormone is available
without prescription,

1107
00:44:35,860 --> 00:44:36,693
over the counter.

1108
00:44:36,693 --> 00:44:38,700
You just go into a pharmacy
or drugstore or order online,

1109
00:44:38,700 --> 00:44:40,410
this hormone, which is known

1110
00:44:40,410 --> 00:44:41,910
to have all these powerful effects.

1111
00:44:41,910 --> 00:44:43,358
So I get very, very concerned

1112
00:44:43,358 --> 00:44:45,720
when I hear about people taking melatonin,

1113
00:44:45,720 --> 00:44:47,430
especially at the levels that are present

1114
00:44:47,430 --> 00:44:48,600
in most supplements.

1115
00:44:48,600 --> 00:44:50,630
It's been recognized for a very long time,

1116
00:44:50,630 --> 00:44:53,590
and in fact, there are now
data to support the fact

1117
00:44:53,590 --> 00:44:56,630
that animals of all
kinds, including humans,

1118
00:44:56,630 --> 00:44:59,890
will seek out mates and
engage in mating behavior

1119
00:44:59,890 --> 00:45:04,190
more frequently during the
long days of spring and summer.

1120
00:45:04,190 --> 00:45:06,860
That's right, in
seasonally-breeding animals,

1121
00:45:06,860 --> 00:45:08,700
of course, this is the case,

1122
00:45:08,700 --> 00:45:10,900
but in humans as well,

1123
00:45:10,900 --> 00:45:13,830
there is more seeking out
of mates and mating behavior

1124
00:45:13,830 --> 00:45:16,890
in longer day times of year.

1125
00:45:16,890 --> 00:45:19,570
Now, you could imagine
at least two mechanisms

1126
00:45:19,570 --> 00:45:21,560
by which this occurs.

1127
00:45:21,560 --> 00:45:25,410
The first mechanism we could
easily map to melatonin

1128
00:45:25,410 --> 00:45:28,040
and the fact that melatonin is suppressive

1129
00:45:28,040 --> 00:45:31,470
to various aspects of the
so-called gonadal axis,

1130
00:45:31,470 --> 00:45:34,050
which is basically a fancy way of saying

1131
00:45:34,050 --> 00:45:37,730
that melatonin inhibits
testosterone and estrogen output

1132
00:45:37,730 --> 00:45:40,150
from the testes and from the ovaries.

1133
00:45:40,150 --> 00:45:42,320
I just want to remind people
that both males and females

1134
00:45:42,320 --> 00:45:44,720
make testosterone and estrogen,

1135
00:45:44,720 --> 00:45:46,330
although in different ratios, typically,

1136
00:45:46,330 --> 00:45:47,640
in males versus females,

1137
00:45:47,640 --> 00:45:50,610
and that both testosterone and estrogen

1138
00:45:50,610 --> 00:45:55,610
are critical for the desire to
mate and for mating behavior.

1139
00:45:55,900 --> 00:45:58,609
There's a broad misconception
that testosterone

1140
00:45:58,609 --> 00:46:00,320
is involved in mating behavior

1141
00:46:00,320 --> 00:46:02,020
and estrogen's involved
in other behaviors,

1142
00:46:02,020 --> 00:46:04,680
but having enough estrogen is critical

1143
00:46:04,680 --> 00:46:05,960
for both males and females

1144
00:46:05,960 --> 00:46:08,080
in order to maintain the desire to mate,

1145
00:46:08,080 --> 00:46:10,210
and indeed the ability to mate.

1146
00:46:10,210 --> 00:46:12,000
I discuss this on the episode

1147
00:46:12,000 --> 00:46:14,360
on optimizing testosterone and estrogen.

1148
00:46:14,360 --> 00:46:15,980
So if you'd like more details on that,

1149
00:46:15,980 --> 00:46:19,340
please see that episode of
the Huberman Lab Podcast.

1150
00:46:19,340 --> 00:46:22,880
Okay, so if melatonin is suppressive

1151
00:46:22,880 --> 00:46:27,410
to the so-called gonadal axis
and reduces overall levels

1152
00:46:27,410 --> 00:46:30,030
of testosterone and estrogen
in males and females

1153
00:46:30,030 --> 00:46:33,560
and a light inhibits melatonin,

1154
00:46:33,560 --> 00:46:36,750
then when there's more light,
then there's less melatonin

1155
00:46:36,750 --> 00:46:39,570
and more hormone output from the gonads.

1156
00:46:39,570 --> 00:46:41,730
And indeed that's how the system works,

1157
00:46:41,730 --> 00:46:43,750
but that's not the entire story.

1158
00:46:43,750 --> 00:46:46,120
It turns out that there is a second

1159
00:46:46,120 --> 00:46:47,820
so-called parallel pathway,

1160
00:46:47,820 --> 00:46:50,550
meaning a different biological pathway

1161
00:46:50,550 --> 00:46:52,340
that operates in parallel

1162
00:46:52,340 --> 00:46:55,500
to the light suppression
of melatonin pathway

1163
00:46:55,500 --> 00:46:58,730
that provides a basis for longer days,

1164
00:46:58,730 --> 00:47:02,080
inspiring more desire to mate
and more mating behavior.

1165
00:47:02,080 --> 00:47:05,270
So if we think of the first
pathway involving melatonin

1166
00:47:05,270 --> 00:47:08,520
as sort of a break on these
reproductive hormones,

1167
00:47:08,520 --> 00:47:11,120
the second mechanism is
more like an accelerator

1168
00:47:11,120 --> 00:47:12,090
on those hormones.

1169
00:47:12,090 --> 00:47:15,110
And yet it still involve light.

1170
00:47:15,110 --> 00:47:18,770
As I'm about to tell you,
in animals such as mice,

1171
00:47:18,770 --> 00:47:20,640
but also in humans,

1172
00:47:20,640 --> 00:47:24,070
exposure to light, in
particular UV blue light,

1173
00:47:24,070 --> 00:47:26,170
so short wavelengths of light,

1174
00:47:26,170 --> 00:47:29,220
can trigger increases in
testosterone and estrogen

1175
00:47:29,220 --> 00:47:30,820
and the desire to mate.

1176
00:47:30,820 --> 00:47:33,670
Now what's especially important
about this accelerator

1177
00:47:33,670 --> 00:47:36,850
on the desire to mate and
mating behavior and hormones

1178
00:47:36,850 --> 00:47:40,950
is that it is driven by exposure to light,

1179
00:47:40,950 --> 00:47:44,770
but it is not the exposure
of light to the eyes.

1180
00:47:44,770 --> 00:47:48,170
It turns out that it is
the exposure of your skin

1181
00:47:48,170 --> 00:47:50,250
to particular wavelengths of light

1182
00:47:50,250 --> 00:47:52,890
that is triggering
increases in the hormones,

1183
00:47:52,890 --> 00:47:54,510
testosterone, and estrogen,

1184
00:47:54,510 --> 00:47:57,060
leading to increased desire to mate.

1185
00:47:57,060 --> 00:47:59,270
As it turns out, your skin,

1186
00:47:59,270 --> 00:48:01,440
which most of us just think of as a way

1187
00:48:01,440 --> 00:48:03,390
to protect the organs of our body

1188
00:48:03,390 --> 00:48:06,340
or something to hang
clothes on or ornaments on,

1189
00:48:06,340 --> 00:48:09,480
if you're somebody who
has earrings and so forth,

1190
00:48:09,480 --> 00:48:12,380
your skin is actually an endocrine organ,

1191
00:48:12,380 --> 00:48:15,220
meaning it is a hormone-producing

1192
00:48:15,220 --> 00:48:17,393
and hormone-influencing organ.

1193
00:48:18,240 --> 00:48:19,700
I promise what I'm about to tell you next

1194
00:48:19,700 --> 00:48:21,560
will forever change the way that you think

1195
00:48:21,560 --> 00:48:25,800
about your skin and light
and the desire to mate,

1196
00:48:25,800 --> 00:48:28,440
and indeed even mating behavior.

1197
00:48:28,440 --> 00:48:30,600
I think the results are best understood

1198
00:48:30,600 --> 00:48:33,030
by simply going through the primary data,

1199
00:48:33,030 --> 00:48:35,400
meaning the actual research on this topic.

1200
00:48:35,400 --> 00:48:37,590
And to do so, I'm going
to review a recent paper

1201
00:48:37,590 --> 00:48:40,000
that was published in
the Journal Cell Reports,

1202
00:48:40,000 --> 00:48:42,120
Cell Press Journal, excellent journal.

1203
00:48:42,120 --> 00:48:44,463
This is a paper that came out in 2021,

1204
00:48:45,420 --> 00:48:48,680
entitled "Skin Exposure to UVB light

1205
00:48:48,680 --> 00:48:53,130
induces a skin, brain, gonad
axis, and sexual behavior.

1206
00:48:53,130 --> 00:48:55,810
And I want to emphasize
that this was a paper

1207
00:48:55,810 --> 00:48:58,220
that focused on mice

1208
00:48:58,220 --> 00:49:00,600
in order to address specific mechanisms,

1209
00:49:00,600 --> 00:49:01,650
because in mice,

1210
00:49:01,650 --> 00:49:04,280
you can so-called knock
out particular genes.

1211
00:49:04,280 --> 00:49:06,640
You can remove particular
genes to understand mechanism.

1212
00:49:06,640 --> 00:49:08,190
You just can't do that in humans

1213
00:49:08,190 --> 00:49:10,000
in any kind of controlled way,

1214
00:49:10,000 --> 00:49:12,200
at least not at this point in time.

1215
00:49:12,200 --> 00:49:15,420
And this study also explores humans

1216
00:49:15,420 --> 00:49:18,323
and looked at human
subjects, both men and women.

1217
00:49:19,380 --> 00:49:22,430
The basic finding of this study was that

1218
00:49:22,430 --> 00:49:26,330
when mice or humans were exposed to UVB,

1219
00:49:26,330 --> 00:49:28,530
meaning ultraviolet blue light,
so shortwave length light

1220
00:49:28,530 --> 00:49:31,010
of the sort that comes
through in sunshine,

1221
00:49:31,010 --> 00:49:34,323
but is also available through
various artificial sources.

1222
00:49:35,950 --> 00:49:38,590
If they received enough exposure

1223
00:49:38,590 --> 00:49:40,093
of that light to their skin,

1224
00:49:41,320 --> 00:49:44,870
there were increases in
testosterone that were observed

1225
00:49:44,870 --> 00:49:47,030
within a very brief period of time,

1226
00:49:47,030 --> 00:49:50,120
also increases in the hormone estrogen.

1227
00:49:50,120 --> 00:49:52,577
And I should point out that
the proper ratios of estrogen

1228
00:49:52,577 --> 00:49:55,850
and testosterone were maintained
in both males and females,

1229
00:49:55,850 --> 00:49:58,760
at least as far as these data indicate,

1230
00:49:58,760 --> 00:50:03,760
and mice tended to seek out
mating more and mate more.

1231
00:50:04,480 --> 00:50:07,630
There were also increases
in gonadal weight,

1232
00:50:07,630 --> 00:50:11,300
literally increases in testy
size and in ovarian size

1233
00:50:11,300 --> 00:50:14,080
when mice were exposed to this UVB light

1234
00:50:14,080 --> 00:50:15,540
past a certain threshold.

1235
00:50:15,540 --> 00:50:18,200
Now, as I mentioned before, the
study also looked at humans.

1236
00:50:18,200 --> 00:50:21,980
They did not look at
testy size or ovarian size

1237
00:50:21,980 --> 00:50:23,300
in the human subjects.

1238
00:50:23,300 --> 00:50:25,280
However, because they're humans,

1239
00:50:25,280 --> 00:50:29,000
they did address the psychology
of these human beings

1240
00:50:29,000 --> 00:50:31,470
and addressed whether or
not they had increases

1241
00:50:31,470 --> 00:50:34,840
in, for instance, aggressiveness
or in passionate feelings

1242
00:50:34,840 --> 00:50:38,700
and how their perception
of other people changed

1243
00:50:38,700 --> 00:50:42,360
when they were getting a
lot of UVB light exposure

1244
00:50:42,360 --> 00:50:43,240
to the skin.

1245
00:50:43,240 --> 00:50:45,390
So before I get into some of
the more important details

1246
00:50:45,390 --> 00:50:47,080
of the study and how it was done

1247
00:50:47,080 --> 00:50:49,790
and how you can leverage this
information for yourself,

1248
00:50:49,790 --> 00:50:51,133
if you desire,

1249
00:50:52,040 --> 00:50:55,650
I just want to highlight some
of the basic findings overall.

1250
00:50:55,650 --> 00:50:59,410
UVB exposure increased these
so-called sex steroid levels

1251
00:50:59,410 --> 00:51:00,720
in mice and humans.

1252
00:51:00,720 --> 00:51:03,810
The sex steroid hormones,
when we say steroids,

1253
00:51:03,810 --> 00:51:06,530
we don't mean anabolic
steroids taken exogenously.

1254
00:51:06,530 --> 00:51:07,920
I think when people
hear the word steroids,

1255
00:51:07,920 --> 00:51:10,955
they always think steroid
abuse or use, rather.

1256
00:51:10,955 --> 00:51:13,930
Steroid hormones, such as
testosterone and estrogen,

1257
00:51:13,930 --> 00:51:18,002
went up when mice or humans
had a lot of UVB exposure

1258
00:51:18,002 --> 00:51:19,250
to their skin.

1259
00:51:19,250 --> 00:51:22,810
Second of all, UVB light
exposure to the skin

1260
00:51:22,810 --> 00:51:24,660
enhanced female attractiveness,

1261
00:51:24,660 --> 00:51:27,820
so the perceived attractiveness
of females by males,

1262
00:51:27,820 --> 00:51:30,120
and increased the receptiveness

1263
00:51:30,120 --> 00:51:33,390
or the desire to mate in both sexes.

1264
00:51:33,390 --> 00:51:36,680
UVB light exposure also
changed various aspects

1265
00:51:36,680 --> 00:51:39,050
of female biology related to fertility,

1266
00:51:39,050 --> 00:51:41,530
in particular follicle growth.

1267
00:51:41,530 --> 00:51:43,800
Follicle and egg maturation

1268
00:51:43,800 --> 00:51:47,310
are well-known indices of fertility,

1269
00:51:47,310 --> 00:51:49,760
and of course, correlate
with the menstrual cycle

1270
00:51:49,760 --> 00:51:52,900
in adult humans and is related overall

1271
00:51:52,900 --> 00:51:56,367
to the propensity to become pregnant.

1272
00:51:56,367 --> 00:51:59,390
UVB light exposure enhanced
maturation of the follicle,

1273
00:51:59,390 --> 00:52:02,580
which just meant that more
healthy eggs were being produced.

1274
00:52:02,580 --> 00:52:03,940
These are impressive effects.

1275
00:52:03,940 --> 00:52:05,900
First of all, they
looked at a large number

1276
00:52:05,900 --> 00:52:07,200
of variables in the study.

1277
00:52:07,200 --> 00:52:08,120
And the fact that they looked

1278
00:52:08,120 --> 00:52:10,190
at mice and humans is terrific.

1279
00:52:10,190 --> 00:52:13,100
I think that oftentimes we
find it hard to translate data

1280
00:52:13,100 --> 00:52:13,950
from mice to humans.

1281
00:52:13,950 --> 00:52:16,310
So the fact that they
looked at both in parallel

1282
00:52:16,310 --> 00:52:17,193
is wonderful.

1283
00:52:18,490 --> 00:52:20,300
In the mice and in the humans,

1284
00:52:20,300 --> 00:52:22,800
they established a protocol

1285
00:52:22,800 --> 00:52:26,950
that essentially involved
exposing the skin to UV light

1286
00:52:26,950 --> 00:52:29,440
that was equivalent to
about 20 to 30 minutes

1287
00:52:29,440 --> 00:52:31,380
of midday sun exposure.

1288
00:52:31,380 --> 00:52:33,090
Now, of course, where
you live in the world

1289
00:52:33,090 --> 00:52:34,730
will dictate whether
or not that midday sun

1290
00:52:34,730 --> 00:52:37,670
is very, very bright and
intense or is less bright.

1291
00:52:37,670 --> 00:52:39,400
Maybe there's cloud cover, et cetera.

1292
00:52:39,400 --> 00:52:43,130
But since I'm imagining that
most people are interested

1293
00:52:43,130 --> 00:52:45,730
in the ways to increase testosterone

1294
00:52:45,730 --> 00:52:47,750
and/or estrogen in humans

1295
00:52:47,750 --> 00:52:48,870
and are not so much interested

1296
00:52:48,870 --> 00:52:51,100
in increasing testosterone in mice,

1297
00:52:51,100 --> 00:52:52,850
I'm going to just review what they did

1298
00:52:52,850 --> 00:52:55,940
in the human population
or the human subjects.

1299
00:52:55,940 --> 00:52:58,280
What they did is they had people,

1300
00:52:58,280 --> 00:53:00,070
first of all, establish a baseline.

1301
00:53:00,070 --> 00:53:01,360
And the way they established a baseline

1302
00:53:01,360 --> 00:53:02,670
was a little bit unusual,

1303
00:53:02,670 --> 00:53:04,560
but will make perfect sense to you.

1304
00:53:04,560 --> 00:53:06,020
They had people wear long sleeves

1305
00:53:06,020 --> 00:53:08,820
and essentially cover up and
avoid sunlight for a few days

1306
00:53:08,820 --> 00:53:10,750
so they could measure
their baseline hormones

1307
00:53:10,750 --> 00:53:14,378
in the absence of getting
a lot of UVB light exposure

1308
00:53:14,378 --> 00:53:16,630
from the sun or from other sources.

1309
00:53:16,630 --> 00:53:18,880
Now, of course, these people had access

1310
00:53:18,880 --> 00:53:20,020
to artificial lights,

1311
00:53:20,020 --> 00:53:22,060
but as I've pointed out
on this podcast before,

1312
00:53:22,060 --> 00:53:25,450
it's pretty unusual that
you'll get enough UVB exposure

1313
00:53:25,450 --> 00:53:28,030
from artificial lights throughout the day.

1314
00:53:28,030 --> 00:53:30,710
And in the morning you
need a lot of UVB exposure,

1315
00:53:30,710 --> 00:53:34,110
or we should be getting a lot
of UVB exposure to our eyes

1316
00:53:34,110 --> 00:53:36,050
and to our face and to our
skin throughout the day,

1317
00:53:36,050 --> 00:53:37,740
provided we're not getting sunburnt.

1318
00:53:37,740 --> 00:53:40,220
This is actually a healthy
thing for mood and for energy

1319
00:53:40,220 --> 00:53:41,220
throughout the day.

1320
00:53:41,220 --> 00:53:43,940
It's only at night,
basically between the hours

1321
00:53:43,940 --> 00:53:46,310
of about 10:00 pm and 4:00 am,

1322
00:53:46,310 --> 00:53:49,740
that even a tiny bit of UVB
exposure from artificial sources

1323
00:53:49,740 --> 00:53:51,667
can mess us up in terms of our sleep

1324
00:53:51,667 --> 00:53:53,460
and our energy levels, and so on.

1325
00:53:53,460 --> 00:53:55,880
And that's because of
the potent effect of UVB

1326
00:53:55,880 --> 00:53:58,080
on suppressing melatonin.

1327
00:53:58,080 --> 00:54:01,220
So the point here is that
they establish a baseline

1328
00:54:01,220 --> 00:54:04,230
whereby people were getting
some artificial light exposure

1329
00:54:04,230 --> 00:54:05,063
throughout the day,

1330
00:54:05,063 --> 00:54:06,690
but they weren't getting outside a lot.

1331
00:54:06,690 --> 00:54:08,380
They weren't getting a lot of sunlight.

1332
00:54:08,380 --> 00:54:11,750
And then they had people receive a dose

1333
00:54:11,750 --> 00:54:14,060
of UVB light exposure

1334
00:54:14,060 --> 00:54:16,860
that was about 20 to 30 minutes outdoors.

1335
00:54:16,860 --> 00:54:20,350
They had people wear short
sleeves, no hat, no sunglasses.

1336
00:54:20,350 --> 00:54:21,920
Some people wore sleeveless shirts.

1337
00:54:21,920 --> 00:54:23,610
They encouraged people to wear shorts.

1338
00:54:23,610 --> 00:54:26,010
So they were indeed wearing clothing.

1339
00:54:26,010 --> 00:54:27,400
They were not naked.

1340
00:54:27,400 --> 00:54:30,310
And they were wearing
clothing that was culturally

1341
00:54:30,310 --> 00:54:31,470
and situationally appropriate,

1342
00:54:31,470 --> 00:54:32,980
at least for the part of the world

1343
00:54:32,980 --> 00:54:34,390
where this study was done.

1344
00:54:34,390 --> 00:54:37,150
And they had people do that
two or three times a week.

1345
00:54:37,150 --> 00:54:38,370
So in terms of a protocol

1346
00:54:38,370 --> 00:54:39,890
that you might export from this study,

1347
00:54:39,890 --> 00:54:42,040
basically getting outside
for about 30 minutes,

1348
00:54:42,040 --> 00:54:44,730
two or three times a week
in a minimum of clothing,

1349
00:54:44,730 --> 00:54:47,220
and yet still wearing enough clothing

1350
00:54:47,220 --> 00:54:48,970
that is culturally appropriate.

1351
00:54:48,970 --> 00:54:51,210
They were outside, they
weren't sun bathing,

1352
00:54:51,210 --> 00:54:52,620
flipping over on their back and front.

1353
00:54:52,620 --> 00:54:53,870
They were just moving about doing things.

1354
00:54:53,870 --> 00:54:55,440
They could read, they could talk,

1355
00:54:55,440 --> 00:54:57,560
they could go about other activities,

1356
00:54:57,560 --> 00:54:59,590
but they weren't wearing a broad brim hat

1357
00:54:59,590 --> 00:55:00,580
or a hat of any kind,

1358
00:55:00,580 --> 00:55:03,750
just getting a lot of sun
exposure to their skin.

1359
00:55:03,750 --> 00:55:08,030
They did this for a total
of 10 to 12 UVB treatments.

1360
00:55:08,030 --> 00:55:10,100
So this took several weeks, right?

1361
00:55:10,100 --> 00:55:11,450
It took about a month,
if you think about it,

1362
00:55:11,450 --> 00:55:12,380
two or three times per week

1363
00:55:12,380 --> 00:55:15,810
for a total of 10 to 12 UVB treatments.

1364
00:55:15,810 --> 00:55:17,330
These treatments, of course,
are just being outside

1365
00:55:17,330 --> 00:55:18,420
in the sun.

1366
00:55:18,420 --> 00:55:20,900
And then they measured hormones,

1367
00:55:20,900 --> 00:55:22,120
and they measured the psychology

1368
00:55:22,120 --> 00:55:24,950
of these male and female adult subjects.

1369
00:55:24,950 --> 00:55:27,110
Let's first look at the
psychological changes

1370
00:55:27,110 --> 00:55:28,980
that these human subjects experienced

1371
00:55:28,980 --> 00:55:33,090
after getting 10 to 12 of
these UVB light exposure

1372
00:55:33,090 --> 00:55:35,410
outdoor and sunlight type treatments.

1373
00:55:35,410 --> 00:55:37,120
They did this by collecting blood samples

1374
00:55:37,120 --> 00:55:38,430
throughout the study,

1375
00:55:38,430 --> 00:55:40,990
and they saw significant increases

1376
00:55:40,990 --> 00:55:42,730
in the hormones, beta-estradiol,

1377
00:55:42,730 --> 00:55:45,270
which is one of the
major forms of estrogen,

1378
00:55:45,270 --> 00:55:48,450
progesterone, another
important steroid hormone,

1379
00:55:48,450 --> 00:55:51,720
and testosterone in both men and women.

1380
00:55:51,720 --> 00:55:55,240
Now, an important point is
that the testosterone increases

1381
00:55:55,240 --> 00:55:59,330
were significantly higher in
men that happened to originate

1382
00:55:59,330 --> 00:56:03,030
from countries that had low UV exposure

1383
00:56:04,080 --> 00:56:05,560
compared to individuals from countries

1384
00:56:05,560 --> 00:56:07,970
with high UV exposure.

1385
00:56:07,970 --> 00:56:10,110
Now, this ought to make sense

1386
00:56:10,110 --> 00:56:11,370
if we understand a little bit

1387
00:56:11,370 --> 00:56:14,010
about how the skin functions
as an endocrine organ.

1388
00:56:14,010 --> 00:56:17,070
Many of you have probably
heard of vitamin D3,

1389
00:56:17,070 --> 00:56:19,730
which is a vitamin that we all make.

1390
00:56:19,730 --> 00:56:21,210
Many people supplement it as well

1391
00:56:21,210 --> 00:56:23,133
if they need additional vitamin D3.

1392
00:56:24,320 --> 00:56:28,840
We all require sunlight in
order to allow vitamin D3

1393
00:56:28,840 --> 00:56:32,200
to be synthesized and perform
its roles in the body.

1394
00:56:32,200 --> 00:56:35,150
And it turns out that
people who have darker skin

1395
00:56:35,150 --> 00:56:39,730
actually need more vitamin D3
and/or more sunlight exposure

1396
00:56:39,730 --> 00:56:42,220
in order to activate that D3 pathway,

1397
00:56:42,220 --> 00:56:45,300
than do people with paler skin.

1398
00:56:45,300 --> 00:56:47,490
And this should make sense to all of you

1399
00:56:47,490 --> 00:56:50,190
given what you now
understand about melanocytes,

1400
00:56:50,190 --> 00:56:51,760
that cell type that we discussed earlier,

1401
00:56:51,760 --> 00:56:54,840
because melanocytes have
pigment within them.

1402
00:56:54,840 --> 00:56:56,670
And if you have darker skin,

1403
00:56:56,670 --> 00:56:59,300
it means that you have more melanocytes

1404
00:56:59,300 --> 00:57:00,580
or that you have melanocytes

1405
00:57:00,580 --> 00:57:03,990
that are more efficient
at creating pigment.

1406
00:57:03,990 --> 00:57:06,010
And as a consequence,

1407
00:57:06,010 --> 00:57:06,909
the light that lands on your skin

1408
00:57:06,909 --> 00:57:09,420
will be absorbed by those melanocytes,

1409
00:57:09,420 --> 00:57:12,750
and less of it is able
to impact the D3 pathway.

1410
00:57:12,750 --> 00:57:14,070
Whereas if you have pale skin,

1411
00:57:14,070 --> 00:57:16,110
more of the light that lands on your skin

1412
00:57:16,110 --> 00:57:18,200
can trigger the synthesis

1413
00:57:18,200 --> 00:57:22,370
and assist the actions of vitamin D3.

1414
00:57:22,370 --> 00:57:24,350
Similarly, in this study, they found

1415
00:57:24,350 --> 00:57:25,183
that people who had paler skin

1416
00:57:25,183 --> 00:57:28,210
and/or who originated from countries

1417
00:57:28,210 --> 00:57:32,300
where they had less UVB light
exposure across the year

1418
00:57:32,300 --> 00:57:35,530
had greater, meaning more
significant, increases

1419
00:57:35,530 --> 00:57:36,970
in testosterone overall

1420
00:57:36,970 --> 00:57:39,640
than did people who
already were getting a lot

1421
00:57:39,640 --> 00:57:41,120
of UVB exposure.

1422
00:57:41,120 --> 00:57:43,850
This led them to explore
so-called seasonal changes

1423
00:57:43,850 --> 00:57:46,440
in testosterone that occurred normally

1424
00:57:46,440 --> 00:57:49,710
in the absence of any
light exposure treatment.

1425
00:57:49,710 --> 00:57:52,660
So up until now, I've been
talking about the aspects

1426
00:57:52,660 --> 00:57:55,180
of this study involving
people getting outside

1427
00:57:55,180 --> 00:57:58,010
for about 20 to 30 minutes
per day in sunlight,

1428
00:57:58,010 --> 00:57:59,470
in a minimum of clothing.

1429
00:57:59,470 --> 00:58:01,870
There was an increase
in testosterone observed

1430
00:58:01,870 --> 00:58:03,300
in both men and women.

1431
00:58:03,300 --> 00:58:05,320
The increases in testosterone were greater

1432
00:58:05,320 --> 00:58:08,560
for people that had paler
skin than darker skin.

1433
00:58:08,560 --> 00:58:10,270
So the data I'm about to describe

1434
00:58:10,270 --> 00:58:13,030
also come from this same
paper, but do not involve

1435
00:58:13,030 --> 00:58:16,130
20 to 30 minute daily
sun exposure protocols.

1436
00:58:16,130 --> 00:58:19,680
It's simply addressing whether
or not testosterone levels

1437
00:58:19,680 --> 00:58:22,563
change as a function of time of year.

1438
00:58:24,010 --> 00:58:27,860
They measure testosterone
across the 12-month calendar.

1439
00:58:27,860 --> 00:58:29,700
This study was done on subjects living

1440
00:58:29,700 --> 00:58:32,230
in the Northern Hemisphere
for the entire year.

1441
00:58:32,230 --> 00:58:35,540
And so in the months of
January, February, and March,

1442
00:58:35,540 --> 00:58:38,650
of course, the length of days is shortest

1443
00:58:38,650 --> 00:58:41,100
and the length of nights is longest.

1444
00:58:41,100 --> 00:58:43,640
And, of course, in the
spring and summer months,

1445
00:58:43,640 --> 00:58:45,750
June, July, August, September, and so on,

1446
00:58:45,750 --> 00:58:47,780
the days are much longer
and the nights are shorter.

1447
00:58:47,780 --> 00:58:50,603
And what they observed was very obvious.

1448
00:58:51,610 --> 00:58:54,620
They observed that testosterone levels

1449
00:58:54,620 --> 00:58:56,820
were lowest in the winter months

1450
00:58:56,820 --> 00:58:58,420
and were highest in the months

1451
00:58:58,420 --> 00:59:01,280
of June, July, August, and September.

1452
00:59:01,280 --> 00:59:03,080
Now, these are very important data.

1453
00:59:03,080 --> 00:59:03,913
At least to my knowledge,

1454
00:59:03,913 --> 00:59:07,490
these are the first data
systematically exploring the levels

1455
00:59:07,490 --> 00:59:10,000
of sex steroid hormones in humans

1456
00:59:10,000 --> 00:59:11,620
as a function of time of year

1457
00:59:11,620 --> 00:59:13,450
and thereby as a function

1458
00:59:13,450 --> 00:59:16,000
of how much sunlight
exposure they're getting.

1459
00:59:16,000 --> 00:59:17,950
And what's remarkable about these data

1460
00:59:17,950 --> 00:59:20,680
is that they map very
well to the data in mice

1461
00:59:20,680 --> 00:59:23,600
and the other data in
this paper on humans,

1462
00:59:23,600 --> 00:59:28,040
which illustrate that if you're
getting more UVB exposure,

1463
00:59:28,040 --> 00:59:29,810
your testosterone levels are higher.

1464
00:59:29,810 --> 00:59:31,090
This study went a step further

1465
00:59:31,090 --> 00:59:33,780
and explored whether or not
the amount of sunlight exposure

1466
00:59:33,780 --> 00:59:35,270
that one is getting to their skin

1467
00:59:35,270 --> 00:59:37,420
influences their psychology

1468
00:59:37,420 --> 00:59:40,130
in terms of whether or not
they have increased desire

1469
00:59:40,130 --> 00:59:41,600
to mate and so on.

1470
00:59:41,600 --> 00:59:43,970
It's well known that sunlight exposure

1471
00:59:43,970 --> 00:59:46,810
to the eyes can increase mood.

1472
00:59:46,810 --> 00:59:48,775
And I talked about this
in the podcast episode

1473
00:59:48,775 --> 00:59:50,684
with my guest, Dr. Samer Hattar,

1474
00:59:50,684 --> 00:59:52,800
who's the director of
the chronobiology unit

1475
00:59:52,800 --> 00:59:54,430
at the National Institutes
of Mental Health.

1476
00:59:54,430 --> 00:59:55,720
And Samer's recommendation

1477
00:59:55,720 --> 00:59:57,550
is that people get as
much bright light exposure

1478
00:59:57,550 --> 01:00:00,230
as they safely can in the
morning and throughout the day

1479
01:00:00,230 --> 01:00:02,450
for sake of both sleep and energy,

1480
01:00:02,450 --> 01:00:06,900
but also for enhancing mood
and regulating appetite.

1481
01:00:06,900 --> 01:00:08,840
In this study, it was found

1482
01:00:08,840 --> 01:00:12,030
that both males and
females had higher levels

1483
01:00:12,030 --> 01:00:16,180
of romantic passion after
getting the UV treatment.

1484
01:00:16,180 --> 01:00:18,760
In fact, some of them reported
increases in romantic passion

1485
01:00:18,760 --> 01:00:21,490
from just one or two
of these UV treatments.

1486
01:00:21,490 --> 01:00:24,580
So they didn't have to go
through all 10 or 12 in order

1487
01:00:24,580 --> 01:00:28,430
to get a statistically
significant increase in passion.

1488
01:00:28,430 --> 01:00:30,060
Now, when we talk about passion,

1489
01:00:30,060 --> 01:00:32,030
as the authors of this paper acknowledge,

1490
01:00:32,030 --> 01:00:32,990
there's really two forms.

1491
01:00:32,990 --> 01:00:34,690
There is emotional and sexual,

1492
01:00:34,690 --> 01:00:36,440
and they parse this pretty finely.

1493
01:00:36,440 --> 01:00:37,980
I don't want to go into all the details,

1494
01:00:37,980 --> 01:00:39,760
and we can provide a reference
and link to this study

1495
01:00:39,760 --> 01:00:41,760
if you'd like to look at those details.

1496
01:00:41,760 --> 01:00:44,610
But what they found was that women

1497
01:00:44,610 --> 01:00:46,710
receiving this UVB light exposure

1498
01:00:47,700 --> 01:00:49,550
focused more on increases

1499
01:00:49,550 --> 01:00:51,780
in physical arousal and sexual passion,

1500
01:00:51,780 --> 01:00:53,750
whereas the men actually scored higher

1501
01:00:53,750 --> 01:00:55,620
on the cognitive dimensions of passion,

1502
01:00:55,620 --> 01:00:58,260
such as obsessive thoughts
about their partner and so on.

1503
01:00:58,260 --> 01:01:00,680
Regardless, both males and females

1504
01:01:01,560 --> 01:01:05,450
experienced and reported a
increase in sexual passion

1505
01:01:05,450 --> 01:01:06,920
and desire to mate.

1506
01:01:06,920 --> 01:01:08,660
And we now know there were increases

1507
01:01:08,660 --> 01:01:10,520
in testosterone and estrogen,

1508
01:01:10,520 --> 01:01:13,230
which of course could be driving
the psychological changes,

1509
01:01:13,230 --> 01:01:15,860
although I'm sure that those
interact in both directions,

1510
01:01:15,860 --> 01:01:19,430
meaning the hormones no
doubt affect psychology

1511
01:01:19,430 --> 01:01:21,240
and no doubt the psychology,

1512
01:01:21,240 --> 01:01:22,990
these changes in passionate feelings,

1513
01:01:22,990 --> 01:01:24,910
no doubt also increased

1514
01:01:24,910 --> 01:01:26,950
or changed the hormone levels as well.

1515
01:01:26,950 --> 01:01:29,410
And I want to reemphasize

1516
01:01:29,410 --> 01:01:31,430
that there was a component of the study

1517
01:01:31,430 --> 01:01:35,320
that had no deliberate
daylight, sunlight exposure

1518
01:01:35,320 --> 01:01:36,380
for 20 or 30 minutes,

1519
01:01:36,380 --> 01:01:39,630
but rather just looked at hormone
levels throughout the year

1520
01:01:39,630 --> 01:01:44,020
and found that the increase in day length

1521
01:01:44,020 --> 01:01:45,460
correlated with increases

1522
01:01:45,460 --> 01:01:47,450
in testosterone and sexual passion.

1523
01:01:47,450 --> 01:01:50,180
Now, in my opinion, this
is a very noteworthy study

1524
01:01:50,180 --> 01:01:54,360
because it really illustrates
that sunlight and day length

1525
01:01:54,360 --> 01:01:56,430
can impact the melatonin pathway

1526
01:01:56,430 --> 01:01:59,640
and thereby take the foot off the brake,

1527
01:01:59,640 --> 01:02:02,617
so to speak, on testosterone, estrogen,

1528
01:02:02,617 --> 01:02:04,010
and the desire to mate.

1529
01:02:04,010 --> 01:02:08,250
It also emphasizes that
sunlight, UVB light,

1530
01:02:08,250 --> 01:02:11,400
can directly trigger hormone pathways

1531
01:02:11,400 --> 01:02:14,130
and desire to mate and mating behavior.

1532
01:02:14,130 --> 01:02:15,530
Now, this study went a step further

1533
01:02:15,530 --> 01:02:17,540
in defining the precise mechanism

1534
01:02:17,540 --> 01:02:19,537
by which light can
impact all these hormones

1535
01:02:19,537 --> 01:02:21,600
and this desire to mate.

1536
01:02:21,600 --> 01:02:23,700
And here, understanding
the mechanism is key

1537
01:02:23,700 --> 01:02:26,170
if you want to export
a particular protocol

1538
01:02:26,170 --> 01:02:27,853
or tool that you might apply.

1539
01:02:29,340 --> 01:02:32,470
We talked earlier about how
UVB light exposure to the eyes

1540
01:02:32,470 --> 01:02:34,610
triggers activation of
these particular neurons

1541
01:02:34,610 --> 01:02:35,670
within the eye,

1542
01:02:35,670 --> 01:02:37,940
and then with centers deeper in the brain,

1543
01:02:37,940 --> 01:02:39,820
and eventually the pineal gland

1544
01:02:39,820 --> 01:02:42,200
to suppress the output of melatonin

1545
01:02:42,200 --> 01:02:45,070
and thereby to allow
testosterone and estrogen

1546
01:02:45,070 --> 01:02:46,230
to exist at higher levels

1547
01:02:46,230 --> 01:02:50,620
because melatonin can inhibit
testosterone and estrogen.

1548
01:02:50,620 --> 01:02:51,700
In this study,

1549
01:02:51,700 --> 01:02:54,140
they were able to very clearly establish

1550
01:02:54,140 --> 01:02:57,490
that it is sunlight exposure to our skin

1551
01:02:57,490 --> 01:02:59,470
that is causing these hormone increases

1552
01:02:59,470 --> 01:03:02,150
that they observed in mice and humans.

1553
01:03:02,150 --> 01:03:03,610
And the way they did that

1554
01:03:03,610 --> 01:03:06,690
was to use the so-called
knockout technology,

1555
01:03:06,690 --> 01:03:08,730
the ability to remove specific genes

1556
01:03:08,730 --> 01:03:11,110
within specific tissues of the body.

1557
01:03:11,110 --> 01:03:13,650
And what they found is that UVB light,

1558
01:03:13,650 --> 01:03:16,483
meaning sunlight-exposed skin,

1559
01:03:17,420 --> 01:03:19,530
upregulated, meaning
increased the activity

1560
01:03:19,530 --> 01:03:21,030
of something called p53,

1561
01:03:21,030 --> 01:03:24,060
which is involved in
the maturation of cells

1562
01:03:24,060 --> 01:03:26,030
and various aspects of cellular function.

1563
01:03:26,030 --> 01:03:29,890
And the cells they were focused
on were the keratinocytes,

1564
01:03:29,890 --> 01:03:32,560
which you are now familiar with
from our earlier discussion

1565
01:03:32,560 --> 01:03:35,140
about the fact that the
epidermis of your skin

1566
01:03:35,140 --> 01:03:38,013
contains mainly keratinocytes
and melanocytes.

1567
01:03:38,950 --> 01:03:43,060
Sunlight exposure increased
p53 activity in the skin.

1568
01:03:43,060 --> 01:03:48,060
And p53 activity was required
for the downstream increases

1569
01:03:48,060 --> 01:03:51,030
in ovarian size, in testicular size,

1570
01:03:51,030 --> 01:03:55,580
in testosterone increases,
in the estrogen increases,

1571
01:03:55,580 --> 01:03:57,310
and the various other changes

1572
01:03:57,310 --> 01:04:00,020
that they observed at
the physiological level

1573
01:04:00,020 --> 01:04:03,110
when animals or humans
were exposed to sunlight.

1574
01:04:03,110 --> 01:04:04,960
So these data are important
because what they mean

1575
01:04:04,960 --> 01:04:06,950
is that not only is it important

1576
01:04:06,950 --> 01:04:09,870
that we get sunlight
exposure early in the day

1577
01:04:09,870 --> 01:04:11,690
and throughout the day to our eyes,

1578
01:04:11,690 --> 01:04:14,050
at least as much as is safely possible,

1579
01:04:14,050 --> 01:04:16,750
but that we also need to
get UVB sunlight exposure

1580
01:04:16,750 --> 01:04:21,070
onto our skin if we want to
activate this p53 pathway

1581
01:04:21,070 --> 01:04:25,690
in keratinocytes and the
testosterone and estrogen increases

1582
01:04:25,690 --> 01:04:28,430
that are downstream of that p53 pathway.

1583
01:04:28,430 --> 01:04:33,270
So even though the gene knockout
studies were done on mice,

1584
01:04:33,270 --> 01:04:36,630
they clearly show that if
you remove p53 from the skin,

1585
01:04:36,630 --> 01:04:39,240
that these effects simply do not occur.

1586
01:04:39,240 --> 01:04:41,640
So in terms of thinking about a protocol

1587
01:04:41,640 --> 01:04:43,560
to increase testosterone and estrogen,

1588
01:04:43,560 --> 01:04:45,900
mood and feelings of passion,

1589
01:04:45,900 --> 01:04:47,800
the idea is that you would want

1590
01:04:47,800 --> 01:04:51,600
to get these two to
three exposures per week,

1591
01:04:51,600 --> 01:04:55,510
minimum of 20 to 30 minutes
of sunlight exposure

1592
01:04:55,510 --> 01:04:57,490
onto as much of your body

1593
01:04:57,490 --> 01:04:59,840
as you can reasonably expose it to.

1594
01:04:59,840 --> 01:05:02,080
And when I say reasonably, I mean,

1595
01:05:02,080 --> 01:05:04,410
of course you have to
obey cultural constraints,

1596
01:05:04,410 --> 01:05:05,710
decency constraints.

1597
01:05:05,710 --> 01:05:08,690
And of course you have
to also obey the fact

1598
01:05:08,690 --> 01:05:10,660
that sunlight can burn your skin.

1599
01:05:10,660 --> 01:05:12,967
So many people are probably going to ask,

1600
01:05:12,967 --> 01:05:15,250
"What happens if you wear sunscreen?"

1601
01:05:15,250 --> 01:05:19,730
Well, in theory, because
sunscreen has UV protection,

1602
01:05:19,730 --> 01:05:21,880
it would block some of these effects.

1603
01:05:21,880 --> 01:05:22,713
Now I'm not suggesting

1604
01:05:22,713 --> 01:05:24,620
that people do away
with sunscreen entirely.

1605
01:05:24,620 --> 01:05:27,810
I do hope to do an episode all
about sunscreen in the future

1606
01:05:27,810 --> 01:05:31,000
because sunscreen is a bit
of a controversial topic.

1607
01:05:31,000 --> 01:05:32,760
Skin cancers are a real thing,

1608
01:05:32,760 --> 01:05:35,660
and many people are especially
prone to skin cancer,

1609
01:05:35,660 --> 01:05:37,570
so you need to take that seriously.

1610
01:05:37,570 --> 01:05:39,840
Some people are not very
prone to skin cancers

1611
01:05:39,840 --> 01:05:42,660
and can tolerate much more sun exposure.

1612
01:05:42,660 --> 01:05:44,510
You're probably familiar
with the simple fact

1613
01:05:44,510 --> 01:05:47,930
that if you've gone outside
on the beach with friends,

1614
01:05:47,930 --> 01:05:49,990
some people get burned
very easily, others don't.

1615
01:05:49,990 --> 01:05:52,470
So you really should prioritize the health

1616
01:05:52,470 --> 01:05:54,880
and the avoidance of sunburn on your skin.

1617
01:05:54,880 --> 01:05:58,780
However, these data and
other data point to the fact

1618
01:05:58,780 --> 01:06:01,540
that we should all probably be striving

1619
01:06:01,540 --> 01:06:04,210
to get more sunlight
exposure onto our skin

1620
01:06:04,210 --> 01:06:05,710
during the winter months

1621
01:06:05,710 --> 01:06:08,970
and still getting sunlight
exposure onto our skin

1622
01:06:08,970 --> 01:06:10,050
in the summer months,

1623
01:06:10,050 --> 01:06:12,800
provided we can do that
without damaging our skin.

1624
01:06:12,800 --> 01:06:15,690
Another set of very impressive
effects of UVB light,

1625
01:06:15,690 --> 01:06:16,780
whether or not it comes from sunlight

1626
01:06:16,780 --> 01:06:18,950
or from an artificial source,

1627
01:06:18,950 --> 01:06:22,440
is the effect of UVB light
on our tolerance for pain.

1628
01:06:22,440 --> 01:06:24,350
It turns out that our tolerance for pain

1629
01:06:24,350 --> 01:06:26,190
varies across the year

1630
01:06:26,190 --> 01:06:29,390
and that our pain tolerance is increased

1631
01:06:29,390 --> 01:06:32,160
in longer day conditions.

1632
01:06:32,160 --> 01:06:34,850
And as we saw with the effects of UVB

1633
01:06:34,850 --> 01:06:36,683
on hormones and mating,

1634
01:06:37,840 --> 01:06:42,237
again, this is occurring
via UVB exposure to the skin

1635
01:06:42,237 --> 01:06:45,160
and UVB exposure to the eyes.

1636
01:06:45,160 --> 01:06:46,750
I want to just describe two studies

1637
01:06:46,750 --> 01:06:49,520
that really capture the
essence of these results.

1638
01:06:49,520 --> 01:06:52,540
I'm going to discuss these in
kind of a top contour fashion.

1639
01:06:52,540 --> 01:06:54,260
I won't go into it as quite as much depth

1640
01:06:54,260 --> 01:06:55,460
as I did the last study,

1641
01:06:55,460 --> 01:06:57,960
but I will provide links
to these studies as well.

1642
01:06:59,010 --> 01:07:00,910
The first study is entitled

1643
01:07:00,910 --> 01:07:04,600
Skin Exposure to Ultraviolet
B Rapidly Activates

1644
01:07:04,600 --> 01:07:07,570
Systemic, Neuroendocrine, and
Immunosuppressive Responses.

1645
01:07:07,570 --> 01:07:08,403
And you might hear that and think,

1646
01:07:08,403 --> 01:07:09,900
"Oh, immunosuppressive that's bad."

1647
01:07:09,900 --> 01:07:14,890
But basically what they observed
is that even one exposure

1648
01:07:14,890 --> 01:07:18,490
to UVB light changed the
output of particular hormones

1649
01:07:18,490 --> 01:07:20,100
and neurochemicals in the body,

1650
01:07:20,100 --> 01:07:23,670
such as corticotropin
hormone and beta-endorphins,

1651
01:07:23,670 --> 01:07:25,750
which are these endogenous opioids.

1652
01:07:25,750 --> 01:07:27,330
We've all heard of the opioid crisis,

1653
01:07:27,330 --> 01:07:29,500
which is people getting
addicted to opioids

1654
01:07:29,500 --> 01:07:32,830
that they are taking in
drug form, pharmaceuticals.

1655
01:07:32,830 --> 01:07:35,090
But here I'm referring to endorphins

1656
01:07:35,090 --> 01:07:37,570
that our body naturally
manufactures and releases

1657
01:07:37,570 --> 01:07:39,110
in order to counter pain

1658
01:07:39,110 --> 01:07:44,110
and act as somewhat of a
psychological soother also,

1659
01:07:44,130 --> 01:07:46,410
because, of course, physical
pain and emotional pain

1660
01:07:46,410 --> 01:07:48,740
are intimately linked
in the brain and body.

1661
01:07:48,740 --> 01:07:51,980
What they found was that
exposure to UVB light

1662
01:07:51,980 --> 01:07:55,080
increased the release of
these beta-endorphins.

1663
01:07:55,080 --> 01:07:56,640
It caused essentially the release

1664
01:07:56,640 --> 01:07:59,410
of an endogenous pain killer.

1665
01:07:59,410 --> 01:08:03,040
Now, a second study that
came out very recently,

1666
01:08:03,040 --> 01:08:04,810
just this last week, in fact,

1667
01:08:04,810 --> 01:08:06,070
published in the journal Neuron,

1668
01:08:06,070 --> 01:08:08,290
Cell Press journal, excellent journal,

1669
01:08:08,290 --> 01:08:10,290
is entitled A Visual Circuit Related

1670
01:08:10,290 --> 01:08:12,420
to the Periaqueductal Gray Area

1671
01:08:12,420 --> 01:08:15,330
for the Antinociceptive Effects
of Bright Light Treatment.

1672
01:08:15,330 --> 01:08:18,010
I'll translate a little
bit of that for you.

1673
01:08:18,010 --> 01:08:21,649
The periaqueductal gray is
a region of the mid-brain

1674
01:08:21,649 --> 01:08:24,179
that contains a lot of neurons

1675
01:08:24,180 --> 01:08:26,890
that can release endogenous opioids,

1676
01:08:26,890 --> 01:08:30,850
things like beta-enkephalin,
things like enkephalin,

1677
01:08:30,850 --> 01:08:32,250
things like mu opioid.

1678
01:08:32,250 --> 01:08:34,359
These are all names of chemicals

1679
01:08:34,359 --> 01:08:35,669
that your body can manufacture

1680
01:08:35,670 --> 01:08:37,649
that act as endogenous pain killers

1681
01:08:37,649 --> 01:08:39,519
and increase your tolerance for pain.

1682
01:08:39,520 --> 01:08:41,930
They actually make you
feel less pain overall

1683
01:08:41,930 --> 01:08:43,779
by shutting down some of the neurons

1684
01:08:43,779 --> 01:08:47,149
that perceive pain or by
reducing their activity.

1685
01:08:47,149 --> 01:08:48,689
Not to a dangerous level, right?

1686
01:08:48,689 --> 01:08:50,169
They're not going to
block the pain response

1687
01:08:50,170 --> 01:08:52,660
so that you burn yourself unnecessarily

1688
01:08:52,660 --> 01:08:54,200
or harm yourself unnecessarily,

1689
01:08:54,200 --> 01:08:57,563
but they act a bit of a
pain killer from the inside.

1690
01:08:59,010 --> 01:09:01,310
If you heard the word antinociceptive,

1691
01:09:01,310 --> 01:09:06,310
nociception is basically
the perception or the way

1692
01:09:06,490 --> 01:09:09,460
in which neurons respond
to painful stimuli.

1693
01:09:09,460 --> 01:09:11,729
So you can think of nociceptive events

1694
01:09:11,729 --> 01:09:14,089
in your nervous system as painful events.

1695
01:09:14,090 --> 01:09:15,760
And there I'm using a broad brush.

1696
01:09:15,760 --> 01:09:17,557
I realized that the
experts in pain will say,

1697
01:09:17,557 --> 01:09:19,550
"Oh, it's not really a pain circuit,"

1698
01:09:19,550 --> 01:09:20,500
et cetera, et cetera.

1699
01:09:20,500 --> 01:09:22,890
But for sake of today's discussion,

1700
01:09:22,890 --> 01:09:26,520
it's fair to say that nociception
is the perception of pain.

1701
01:09:26,520 --> 01:09:29,550
So if this title is A
Visual Circuit Related

1702
01:09:29,550 --> 01:09:31,359
to the Periaqueductal Gray,

1703
01:09:31,359 --> 01:09:34,239
which is this area that releases
these endogenous opioids

1704
01:09:34,240 --> 01:09:36,870
for the antinociceptive,
the anti-pain effects

1705
01:09:36,870 --> 01:09:38,383
of bright light treatment,

1706
01:09:40,180 --> 01:09:41,569
the key finding of this study

1707
01:09:41,569 --> 01:09:46,569
is that it is light landing
on the eyes and captured

1708
01:09:46,779 --> 01:09:49,019
by the specific cells I
was talking about earlier,

1709
01:09:49,020 --> 01:09:51,827
those intrinsically photosensitive
melanopsin ganglion cells

1710
01:09:51,827 --> 01:09:53,100
is the long name for them,

1711
01:09:53,100 --> 01:09:54,950
but these particular neurons in your eye,

1712
01:09:54,950 --> 01:09:57,320
and in my eye incidentally,

1713
01:09:57,320 --> 01:10:00,640
that communicate with
particular brain areas.

1714
01:10:00,640 --> 01:10:01,750
These brain areas have names.

1715
01:10:01,750 --> 01:10:04,090
If you want to know
them, for you aficionados

1716
01:10:04,090 --> 01:10:05,760
or for you ultra curious folks,

1717
01:10:05,760 --> 01:10:08,150
they have names like the ventral
lateral geniculate nucleus

1718
01:10:08,150 --> 01:10:09,620
and the intergeniculate leaflet.

1719
01:10:09,620 --> 01:10:10,820
The names don't matter.

1720
01:10:10,820 --> 01:10:13,430
The point is that light
landing on the eyes

1721
01:10:13,430 --> 01:10:16,740
is captured by these melanopsin cells.

1722
01:10:16,740 --> 01:10:18,040
They absorb that light,

1723
01:10:18,040 --> 01:10:20,250
translate that light
into electrical signals

1724
01:10:20,250 --> 01:10:22,040
that are handed off to areas of the brain,

1725
01:10:22,040 --> 01:10:24,490
such as the ventral geniculate.

1726
01:10:24,490 --> 01:10:27,690
And then the ventral
geniculate communicates

1727
01:10:27,690 --> 01:10:30,320
with this periaqueductal gray area

1728
01:10:30,320 --> 01:10:34,000
to evoke the release of
these endogenous opioids

1729
01:10:34,000 --> 01:10:38,020
that soothe you and lead
to less perception of pain.

1730
01:10:38,020 --> 01:10:39,410
This is a really important study

1731
01:10:39,410 --> 01:10:43,390
because it's long been
known that in longer days

1732
01:10:43,390 --> 01:10:44,670
or in bright light environments,

1733
01:10:44,670 --> 01:10:47,403
we tolerate emotional
and physical pain better.

1734
01:10:48,600 --> 01:10:50,030
Previous studies had shown

1735
01:10:50,030 --> 01:10:53,030
that it is light landing on our skin

1736
01:10:53,030 --> 01:10:55,500
that mediates that
effect, but only in part.

1737
01:10:55,500 --> 01:10:57,440
It couldn't explain the entire effect.

1738
01:10:57,440 --> 01:10:59,420
This very recent study indicates

1739
01:10:59,420 --> 01:11:02,390
that it's also light arriving at the eyes,

1740
01:11:02,390 --> 01:11:05,200
and in this case, again, UVB
light, ultraviolet blue light

1741
01:11:05,200 --> 01:11:07,283
of the sort that comes from sunlight,

1742
01:11:08,400 --> 01:11:11,020
that is triggering these anti-pain

1743
01:11:11,020 --> 01:11:12,740
or pain-relieving pathways.

1744
01:11:12,740 --> 01:11:15,230
So once again, we have
two parallel pathways.

1745
01:11:15,230 --> 01:11:16,360
This is a theme you're going to hear

1746
01:11:16,360 --> 01:11:19,080
over and over and over again,
not just in this episode,

1747
01:11:19,080 --> 01:11:21,510
but in all episodes of
the Huberman Lab Podcast,

1748
01:11:21,510 --> 01:11:24,810
because this is the way that
your brain and body are built.

1749
01:11:24,810 --> 01:11:27,960
Nature rarely relies on one mechanism

1750
01:11:27,960 --> 01:11:30,230
in order to create an
important phenomenon,

1751
01:11:30,230 --> 01:11:32,460
and pain relief is an
important phenomenon.

1752
01:11:32,460 --> 01:11:35,950
So we now have at least two
examples of the potent effects

1753
01:11:35,950 --> 01:11:39,610
of UVB light exposure to
the skin and to the eyes.

1754
01:11:39,610 --> 01:11:44,008
One involving activation of testosterone

1755
01:11:44,008 --> 01:11:46,380
and estrogen pathways,
as it relates to mating,

1756
01:11:46,380 --> 01:11:50,250
and another that relates to
reducing the total amount

1757
01:11:50,250 --> 01:11:51,660
of pain that we experience

1758
01:11:51,660 --> 01:11:54,240
in response to any painful stimuli.

1759
01:11:54,240 --> 01:11:57,190
So for those of you that are
thinking tools and protocols,

1760
01:11:57,190 --> 01:12:00,170
if you're somebody who's
experiencing chronic pain,

1761
01:12:00,170 --> 01:12:01,800
provided you can do it safely,

1762
01:12:01,800 --> 01:12:06,220
try to get some UVB exposure,
ideally from sunlight.

1763
01:12:06,220 --> 01:12:07,960
I think the 20 to 30-minute protocol,

1764
01:12:07,960 --> 01:12:10,570
two or three times per
week is an excellent one,

1765
01:12:10,570 --> 01:12:14,320
seems like a fairly low
dose of UVB light exposure.

1766
01:12:14,320 --> 01:12:17,380
It's hard to imagine getting
much damage to the skin.

1767
01:12:17,380 --> 01:12:19,780
Of course, if you have
very sensitive skin,

1768
01:12:19,780 --> 01:12:22,070
or if you live in an area of the world

1769
01:12:22,070 --> 01:12:23,347
that is very, very bright

1770
01:12:23,347 --> 01:12:26,420
and has intense sunlight at
particular times of year,

1771
01:12:26,420 --> 01:12:27,870
you'll want to be cautious.

1772
01:12:27,870 --> 01:12:30,490
Heed the warnings and
considerations about sunscreen

1773
01:12:30,490 --> 01:12:32,920
that I talked about earlier,
or about wearing a hat.

1774
01:12:32,920 --> 01:12:34,900
But the point is very clear.

1775
01:12:34,900 --> 01:12:38,300
Most of us should be
getting more UVB exposure

1776
01:12:38,300 --> 01:12:39,163
from sunlight.

1777
01:12:40,140 --> 01:12:42,580
I can already hear the
screams within the comments

1778
01:12:42,580 --> 01:12:44,577
or rather the questions
within the comments, saying,

1779
01:12:44,577 --> 01:12:46,260
"Well, what if I live
in a part of the world

1780
01:12:46,260 --> 01:12:48,790
where I don't get much UVB exposure?"

1781
01:12:48,790 --> 01:12:50,989
And I want to emphasize something
that I've also emphasized

1782
01:12:50,989 --> 01:12:53,160
in the many discussions on this podcast

1783
01:12:53,160 --> 01:12:55,500
related to sleep and circadian
rhythms and alertness,

1784
01:12:55,500 --> 01:12:59,410
which is even on a cloud-covered day,

